[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome to The Barry Attack!"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3{ Welcome to the exciting world of the Barry Attack, a direct approach which sidesteps both the King's Indian and Grünfeld making it the ideal opening for the  d -pawn-wielding club or internet players, especially those who like to eschew an early  c2 - c4  angling for some play along the lines of a Colle, London or Torre. }( { The Colle is a bit toothless when Black has a bishop on  g7  and can react with  ...d6  and  ...e5 ; the London and Torre are both better approaches after   }2...g6 { , i.e. }3.Bf4 { and }3.Bg5 { . However, the resulting play may be somewhat drier than those who like to use those openings against }{   }1...d5 { and }1...Nf6 2.Nf3 e6 { might wish. } )( { By contrast, the Barry Attack is far from dry. White plays   }3.Nc3 { preparing to take over the centre with  e2-e4 . Black may allow that and go for the Pirc, but plenty of King's Indian and Grünfeld aficionados don't also defend the Pirc and have been caught out over the years after }3...Bg7 4.e4 { . White isn't just readying the  e -pawn, but also intends to whisk the dark-squared bishop out to  f4 , angling for an aggressive type of London if you prefer. Indeed, that's what generally occurs, since Black usually elects to hold up  e2 - e4  at this point. } )
3. d5
4. Bf4{ There is some debate as to whether this or  3.Nc3  should be considered the starting point of the Barry Attack. There is also a debate over where the name comes from. We're happy to side with Andrew Martin, who was an active and strong player in the 1980s when the opening first really became fashionable. He attributes it to the father of early Barry pioneer Julian Hodgson, who was supposedly told to 'Just give him some Barry'.  Slang definitions of 'Barry' vary, however, ranging from bluff to describing something very good of its type. What we can safely say is that the Barry Attack was a most dangerous weapon in the late 1980s when it was adopted by the English Grandmaster Mark Hebden, who developed the variation over the next 25 years or so, at times almost single-handedly, and remains a dangerous weapon in 2023. That's especially the case at club, internet and tournament level. }( { White can follow up }4.Bf4 { with  Qd2 , the so-called Tarzan Attack, but such a direct approach allows Black fairly easy counterplay with }4...Bg7 5.Qd2 Ne4 { or here }5...O-O 6.Bh6 Bxh6 7.Qxh6 c5 { .  Instead, we prefer the solid traditional set-up involving  e2 - e3  and  Be2 , an approach with may initially look modest - but do keep a close eye on Harry, White's  h -pawn. Indeed, if White can get  Ne5  and  h2 - h4 - h5  in, the result may well be a powerful early initiative. You may also have noticed that the bishop on  f4  gazes at  c7 . } )( { Most certainly,   }4...Nbd7? 5.Nb5! { would be rather embarrassing for Black and, of late, ideas with an early  Nb5  have, in any case, been fairly fashionable for White, as we'll see as an  alternative  to our main line. } )( { Richard can't recall losing a classical game after }4.Bf4 { . The Barry is an opening he has played over 20 such games with and was keen to keep in his repertoire by looking for new ideas in it, many of which you'll find in this course. Simon has played the opening somewhat less, but was also keen to have the Barry in his repertoire as his favourite pawn is, of course, Harry.  The opening can also arise via a Jobava London move order, which he sometimes plays, i.e. }{   }2.Nc3 d5 3.Bf4 { , and if }3...g6 4.Nf3 { or }4.e3 Bg7 5.Nf3 { .  Before we introduce some of the key ideas behind the Barry Attack, we should give a special mention to Mark Hebden, the English GM whose success with the opening on the UK circuit inspired both your authors, as well as a whole host of other players, to take up the opening. Hebden's fellow highly-experienced chess professionals the Czech IM Josef Pribyl, the Czech GM Pavel Blatny, and the Ukrainian-French GM Vladimir Okhotnik, have also done much to refine and promote the opening, as originally did Ian Rogers.  We should also mention the many successes with the Barry of former Women's World Champion Antoaneta Stefanova, while even Magnus Carlsen has been known to dabble in it at blitz.  We do hope you enjoy this course and repertoire, one in which White largely aims to combine aggression with not compromising the pawn structure, as well as plenty of success in your own games with the Barry Attack!  It's now time to enjoy some  classic Barry games!  We suggest you check the first five illustrative games, which should reveal several important motifs for the Barry in general as well as our proposed repertoire, before moving on to tackling the theory, beginning with the  Quickstarter.  That should get you up and running, after which you can turn to tackling the more detailed theoretical coverage and enjoy the remaining illustrative games. } )
