[White "Model Games"]
[Black "(1) Tartakower, S. - Pilnik, H., Amsterdam 1950"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4{ Setting up our favourite Barry formation. }
4. Bg7{ The great Polish player had been dabbling occasionally in the Barry for many a year by 1950. Others who also tried the opening in its early decades include Capablanca, Torre, Colle and Alekhine, but back then White usually preferred a combination of an early  h2 - h3  and  Bd3 , looking to force through a quick  e3 - e4 . For example: }( 4...c6 5.h3!? Bg7 6.e3 { and after }6...O-O 7.Bd3 c5! { , Black gives up a tempo, but equalises, since White's light-squared bishop isn't especially useful on  d3  and even becomes a target in the event of Black recapturing on  c5  with a knight.  More common was }{   }6...Nbd7 { with two main setups for White:   A)  }7.Bd3!? { This would soon be how most strong players wanted to handle the Barry. White aims for  e2 - e4  and  7.Bd3  still looks like a decent move here. }7...O-O 8.O-O Re8 9.Bh2!? { This prophylactic retreat, designed against ... Nh5  ideas, was first seen in Rosselli del Turco-Colle, Paris Olympiad 1924, and is still considered fairly critical. Black's position is slightly congested and White may follow up by seizing space with  a2 - a4 - a5 , as well as by supporting the  e3 - e4  break with  Re1 .   B)  }{   }7.Be2 b6 { when }8.Ne5!? Bb7 9.h4!? { costs a tempo, but is much more in keeping with our preferred method of expansion when allowed in this course.  White would usually go }{   }8.O-O Bb7 9.Ne5 { Having completed development, White leapt forward so, but here Black was pretty solid in Tartakower-Wahltuch, London 1922, and such a plan is better timed when White hasn't already castled kingside. Another plan is }9.a4!? { As White can always double on the  a -file, with  Ra3  and  Qa1 , for instance,  a4 - a5  is now very much a possibility. }9...a5 10.Bd3!? { Losing a tempo with the bishop, but White ought to still be slightly for choice here, since their position is the easier to handle. The main pawn break is  e3 - e4 , which  Re1  will but support, and meanwhile do observe how ... c5  would leave a certain hole on  b5 . } )
5. e3
5. O-O
6. h3{ White's last was very sensible, but there is no need for  h2 - h3  here and simply the undeveloped bishop should prefer to slide up to  e2  instead. }
6. b6( { Returning the favour. }6...c5! 7.Bd3 b6 8.O-O Bb7 { has been shown to be quite a comfortable setup for Black, in part thanks to their control of the key  e4  point. } )( {   }7.Nb5?! Ne4! { This is exactly the kind of  Nb5  raid White should be wary of with Black having castled and got in ... c5 . Black is far from perturbed by the possible invasion on  c7  and even welcomes such a misguided policy: }8.Nc7? e5! 9.Bxe5 Bxe5 10.Nxa8 cxd4 11.exd4 Bf4 { The knight won't make it out alive from  a8  and Black is already doing extremely well. } )
7. Be2
7. Ba6( 7...Bb7 8.h4!? { Again we see White losing a tempo, but still being able to fight for the initiative. Just imagine how good this position would be without the lost tempo - more on that in  Chapter 1A.  Here White intends  Ne5  and waits for Black to develop his queen's knight to  d7 . }( 8.Ne5 Nfd7! { This can be the problem with leaping to  e5  too early. The knight is immediately challenged and Black should have sufficient counterplay. For example: }9.h4 Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Bxe5! 11.dxe5 Nc6 { Black's play against  e5  and with ... d4  leaves White with nothing better than to liquidate on  d5  towards roughly equality. } ) )
8. Ne5{ Now the leap is well-timed as Black can't very easily drop his king's knight back to  d7  and meanwhile,  h3 - h4 - h5  is imminent. }
8. Bxe2( 8...Nfd7? 9.Bxa6 Nxa6 10.Nc6 { White will pick up an important pawn on  d5  and dominate the centre. } )( 8...c5! { As ever, this central challenge must be a critical one. }9.h4 Qc8!? { Black only wants to exchange on  e2  once White has gone  h4 - h5 , which would now entail a gambit. White is by no means forced into such play though: }10.Bxa6 Nxa6 11.Qe2 { Despite the loss of a tempo with the  h -pawn, white may be slightly for choice, since the king will be safe enough on  b1  and in any case  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5  is very much on the way. } )
9. Qxe2
9. Nfd7{ The  d -pawn is poisoned, but this is no longer a good retreat, since White's lead is becoming large in terms of development and space. }
10. O-O-O{ Making the king safe while putting  Nxd5  back on the agenda. }
10. e6( 10...Nxe5 11.Bxe5 { This is usually the best way to recapture when there's no knight on  f6  as an exchange of dark squared bishops should weaken the black king. }11...f6 12.Bg3 { White is clearly for choice, with ideas of not only  h4 - h5 , but very much of blowing open the centre to seize a powerful initiative after  e3 - e4 . } )
11. g4{ Tartakower possibly feared Black obstructing any advance of Harry, but he didn't need to. }( 11.h4! { Sounding the charge would have been fairly strong. White simply wants to get in  h4 - h5  then prepare to invade down the  h -file after an exchange on  g6  and  Qh4 . }11...h5? 12.g4! { Unfortunately for Black, the cure is far worse than the disease. Lines will now open far faster than he can handle. }12...hxg4 13.Nxg4!? { With  Rdg1  and  h4 - h5  on their way, not to mention a timely  e3 - e4 , Black surely wouldn't be able to survive on the kingside. } )
11. c5
12. h4{ Even here White enjoys a dangerous attack, with his king fairly safe on  c1  unlike its counterpart on  g8 . }
12. Nxe5( 12...h6!? { The engines want to try and keep lines closed so, ready to meet  g4 - g5  with ... h5  and  h4 - h5  with ... g5 . As such, White should probably prepare to also hurl the  f -pawn into the fray: }13.Bg3!? Nxe5 14.Bxe5 Bxe5 15.dxe5 Nd7 16.f4 { The position isn't completely clear, but with ideas of a timely  h4 - h5  and even blowing open the position to cause problems down the  d -file with a  Nxd5  sacrifice, White should be for choice. } )
13. Bxe5{ Preparing to eliminate the black king's main defender and already good advice for Black appears hard to come by. }
13. f6( 13...Bxe5 14.dxe5 Nd7 15.f4 { Even here White is clearly better with the strong and simple idea of  g4 - g5  followed by  h4 - h5 . } )( 13...Nd7 14.Bxg7 Kxg7 15.e4! { A timely switch from flank to central play. Black's line-up of pieces on the  d -file doesn't exactly want to see lines opening and his king is still quite weak. For example: }15...cxd4? 16.Rxd4 Qf6 17.Qe3 { White simply intends  g4 - g5  then  h4 - h5  once again. } )
14. Bxb8{ Dropping back to  g3  was obvious and strong, but so good is White's position that this unstereotyped exchange (the important dark-squared bishop for an undeveloped knight) also leaves Tartakower doing pretty well. }
14. Rxb8
15. h5
15. Qd7( 15...g5? 16.h6! Bh8 17.f4 { Revealing one of the key ideas behind White's decision to exchange on  b8 . Black's bishop is entombed and  f4 - f5  is quite the positional threat. } )
16. hxg6
16. hxg6
17. f4{ Having opened the h-file, White both clears a path for the queen to  h2  and prepares to crash through with the  f4 - f5  breakthrough. }
17. Kf7( 17...f5 18.gxf5 Rxf5 19.Qg2 { This leaves Black in some trouble on  g6  (White may also be able to powerfully reroute the knight via  e2 ), but was also a better try than the text move, which is rather a case of jumping out of the frying pan and into the fire. } )
18. f5{ Black's coordination and king position are clearly shot. }
18. Rh8( 18...exf5 19.dxc5! fxg4? 20.Rxd5 { and  Qc4  and/or  Rd6  will follow to clean up the black king. } )
19. Rxh8
19. Rxh8
20. dxc5{ Simple chess, making good use of the rook on  d1  without needing to move it. }
20. exf5( 20...bxc5 21.Qa6! { Even here Black's position would have been on the verge of collapse, with all of  e6  d5  and  a7  under great strain and White even having possibilities of  Ne4 . } )
21. Nxd5
21. Qe6( 21...Qa4 22.Nc3!? Qxg4 23.Rd7+ Kg8 24.c6 { The  c -pawn is simply a winner as the white king always has  d2  if needed. } )
22. gxf5
22. Qxf5
23. Qc4{ Unsurprisingly the discoveries herald the end. }
23. b5
24. Qxb5
24. Rd8
25. c6
25. Qc8
26. Qc5{ Black resigned in view of the multiple threats. }
