1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. b6{ Plenty of Black players like this setup against the Colle, London and Torre, intending a harmonious development with ... Bb7 , ... Nbd7  and ... c5 . Such an approach may work well in those openings, but it doesn't cut the mustard against the Barry Attack. }
7. Ne5{ White takes possession of a key central square and frees the h-pawn for action. Already  h2 - h4 - h5  is imminent and opponents may begin to feel under pressure. }
7. c5( { Obtaining some much-needed counterplay before matters become too serious on the kingside. }7...Bb7?! 8.h4! { Our main game was published in the 40th volume of the august chess journal that is 'Chess Informant'. In the 39th edition, Rogers had annotated a game where he reached this already highly promising position. White appears clearly for choice even if Black challenges for control of the key  e5  point: }8...Nfd7!? 9.h5 Nxe5 { and just as in  the notes  to Tartakower-Pilnik, we prefer the }10.Bxe5! { recapture, looking to exchange off an important defender. We'll return to this position in  Chapter 1A.   After }10.dxe5!? { , Black should continue }10...Nd7! 11.hxg6 hxg6 { White should now move his queen to  d2 , castle queenside and obtain decent play for the  e -pawn. Rogers thought he had something even better, but he had overlooked that Black need not recapture: }12.e6?! Nc5! 13.exf7+ Rxf7 { With ... e5  on the way, Black enjoys promising counterplay and White must always be very careful before electing to give up central control so.  Instead, the game went }{   }10...e6?! 11.hxg6 { when Rogers correctly asserted that }11...hxg6?! 12.Bb5!? { would offer White a very powerful initiative, with  Qg4 - h3  the simple plan, and }11...fxg6 12.Bd3 { left both White's bishops well positioned to aid the attack and he was clearly for choice in Rogers-Pribyl, Tallinn 1985. Note how  Qg4  already represents a serious issue for Black, who is vulnerable on all of  e6 ,  h7  and even  g6 . } )
8. h4{ Boom! White wastes no time in hurling Harry into the fray. As we'll see further in  Chapter 1A,  White is already just doing fairly well. }
8. Bb7
9. h5{ The attack runs on oiled wheels. }
9. Nc6( { An earlier game had actually reached this position and there too Black quickly found things going downhill: }9...cxd4?! 10.exd4 Nbd7 { and now }11.Qd3! { swinging the queen over to  h3  so would have been even stronger, but after }11.hxg6 fxg6 12.Qd2 { , with  Bh6  threatened and  O-O-O  on the way, White enjoyed a promising attack in Lueders-Gollasch, German League 1981. } )
10. hxg6
10. fxg6{ This is a little ugly, but one can hardly fault Black for not wanting to see the whole  h -file open next to her king on  g8 . }
11. Bb5{ It's tempting the force the pace so and this move has been applauded by some previous annotators, but it turns out that  Qf3  is actually not such a powerful threat. }( 11.Qd2! { Retaining the central tension while preparing to castle long leaves White clearly better. He would simply like to go  O-O-O  then perhaps  Rh4  and  Rdh1 , and the queen holds everything together on  d2 , dissuading an exchange on  d4  (when  Bh6  would become even more powerful), while also offering Black a badly misguided leap into  e4 : }11...Ne4? 12.Nxe4 dxe4 13.Bc4+ { Oops! }13...Kh8 14.Nxg6  )
11. Nxe5( { Returning the favour - with interest. }11...Rc8! 12.Bxc6!? Bxc6 13.Qe2 { may still be a little better for White, with ideas of both  O-O-O  and  f2 - f3  followed by  g2 - g4 . }{   }12.Qf3?! cxd4 13.Bxc6! Bxc6 14.exd4 Nh5! { Fearless defence. The following line now appears fairly forced: }15.Qh3! Rxf4 16.Qe6+ Kh8 17.Nxc6 Qe8 18.Ne5 { The position is a complete mess, but the engines reveal their favourite '0.00' assessment, largely because Black has at least an exchange sacrifice on  c3  then check on  e4  to annoy the white king. } )
12. dxe5{ When Black still has a knight on  f6  and the  h -file is open, this is often the right way to recapture on  e5 , driving the knight away from the defence of  h7 . }
12. Nd7
13. Qg4{ The Australian Grandmaster wastes no time in going straight for the black king's throat as it turns out that the  e5 -pawn is poisoned due to the check on  e6 . }
13. Rf5{ Desperate but essential defence as Polgar must plug the  h3 - c8  diagonal. }
14. O-O-O
14. Nxe5( 14...e6 15.e4! { This exploits the potential pressure down the  d -file to destabilise Black's rook and leave her with nothing better than a clearly insufficient exchange sacrifice on  f4 . } )
15. Qh3( { Simple and strong chess as White goes after  h7 . Alternatively, }15.Bxe5!? Bxe5? 16.e4! Rf7 17.Nxd5 { and White's initiative on the light squares and kingside is just too strong. Or }15...Rxe5 16.Bd7! { . Here too Black finds herself under significant pressure. } )
15. h5( 15...Rh5? 16.Qe6+ { This either wins material after exchanges on  h5  or  e5  or leads to a massacre: }16...Nf7 17.Rxh5 gxh5 18.Nxd5 { White dominates the board and unsurprisingly has a decisive initiative. } )
16. Bxe5{ Again, we see this unstereotyped exchange and, again, it's a good one. It's all about opening lines as quickly as possible against the vulnerable black king. }
16. Rxe5( 16...Bxe5? 17.g4! { Since White always has  f2 - f4  in reserve, Black can't maintain a pawn on  h5 . } )
17. f4
17. Rf5
18. e4{ Rogers must have miscalculated here - perhaps he just missed blacks 21st move. }( 18.g4! hxg4 19.Qxg4 { Black might have an unopposed dark-squared bishop and an extra pawn, but her kingside is collapsing and already the engines just can't see a defence. For example: }19...Qd6 20.Bd3 20...Rf6 21.Ne4! { This neat shot decides proceedings. } )
18. Rxf4
19. Qe6+
19. Kh7
20. Nxd5{ It still looks quite scary for Black, but Polgar finds the way to defend. }
20. Bxd5
21. Rxd5
21. Qf8
22. Bd3
22. c4{ A powerful first step in forcing the queens off, after which Black's dark-squared bishop will at last be superior to its light-squared counterpart. }
23. Bxc4
23. Qf6
24. Qxf6
24. Bxf6
25. Bd3
25. Kg7{ A sensible move, if perhaps also a sign that Black was beginning to run low on time. }( 25...Rg4!? { This might have been stronger, aiming to tie White down to  g2 , as well as the  e -pawn. It looks slightly risky, but there is nothing to fear: }26.e5 Bg5+ 27.Kb1 h4 { Black is clearly for choice and may augment the pressure with ... Rf8 - f2 . } )
26. e5
26. Bg5
27. Kb1
27. Raf8{ The first definite misstep. }( 27...a5! 28.Rb5 Rb8 { This looks a little passive, but everything is defended and Black can now probe with ... Rf2  or even consider ideas involving ... Rb4  when the doubled  b -pawns would clamp down well on White's queenside majority. } )
28. Rd7
28. Rf2( 28...Rg4!? 29.Rxa7 Rf2 { This was a more active try although even here, White very much has  c2  secure and shouldn't lose. For example, }30.Rb7 Rfxg2 31.a3 Rg1+ 32.Rxg1 Rxg1+ 33.Ka2 h4 34.Rxb6 Bf4 35.Rb7! { Black is ahead in the race, but White will always have  Be4  if needed and should have enough counterplay. }35...h3!? 36.Rxe7+ Kf8 37.Rh7 h2 38.Be4 Bxe5 39.c4 g5 40.a4 g4 41.Rh5! { White's active rook and a-pawn are in part why the engines now display '0.00', the other reason is shown by: }41...Re1 42.Rxe5 Rxe4 43.Rxe4! h1=Q 44.Rxg4 Qc6 45.Rg3 Qxa4+ 46.Ra3 Qxc4+ 47.Kb1 Ke7 48.Rc3 { This is a well-known fortress and one to remember if you haven't seen it before. The rook shuttles between  a3  and  c3 , and Black's king can't get in. } )
29. Rxa7
29. Rxg2
30. Rb7
30. Be3
31. Rxe7+
31. Rf7
32. Re8{ Keeping pieces on to keep matters as complex as possible in Polgar's presumed time trouble. }
32. Rf8( 32...Bc5! { With ... Re7  on the way, Black hasn't any problems here. } )
33. Re6
33. Rf4( 33...Bc5! 34.a3 Rf7 { Even this looks solid enough for Black, since White will do well to win if a pair of rooks come off. } )
34. a3
34. h4
35. Re7+
35. Kh6( 35...Rf7? 36.Rxf7+ Kxf7 37.Rxh4 { White enjoys excellent winning chances since he will be able to create passed pawns some distance apart after breaking through on the queenside. } )
36. e6{ The  e -pawn looks dangerous, but Polgar now again finds the only defence. }
36. Rg5
37. b4{ Cutting out ... Bc5  possibilities and retaining the tension, as well as good preparation for an advance of the white king. }( 37.Rc7!? Re5 38.e7 Bf2 39.b4! { The engines prefer this more subtle approach, although it's doubtful that even here White can force a win: }39...Kg5! 40.Ka2 Kf6 41.Rc6+ Kxe7 42.Rxg6 Rh5 { White can press but clearly has a lot of work in front of him as the game very much continues. } )
37. Re5
38. Ka2
38. Kg5
39. Re8
39. Rf6( 39...Kf6! 40.Re1 { This may have been what a frantically blitzing Polgar feared, but even here Black is OK so long as she doesn't rush to grab the  e -pawn: }40...g5! 41.e7!? Kf7 { There's no obvious way through for White. } )
40. e7
40. Bf2{ The final mistake. }( 40...Rfe6 41.Rh8 Rxe7 42.R1xh4 { With an exposed king and  g -pawn, this looks far from an easy defence for Black. } )( 40...Bf4!? 41.Rh8 Rxe7 42.R1xh4 Re8!? { Here too White has decent winning chances, but will have to be precise, especially if the  g -pawn begins to run. } )
41. Rf8{ Sacrificing the  e -pawn to win material and the game. }
41. Rxe7
42. Rxf6
42. Kxf6
43. Rf1{ And Polgar resigned. }
