[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2{ The main line and unsurprisingly such a noted theoretician as John Nunn now produces the most critical move. }
6. c5
7. Ne5{ White still dreams of kingside glory. In January 1998, that was a decent approach; nowadays, we suspect that something slightly more subtle is required to cause Black players early problems in this main line of the Barry. }
7. cxd4{ One of two good main moves for Black. }( 7...b6?! 8.h4! { Suddenly  h4 - h5  looms and we're back in  Rogers-Polgar.  } )( 7...Nc6 { Black's other decent approach, swiftly continuing development and as played both before and after this encounter by Nunn:   A)  }8.h4?! { This is, of course, the move that White would like to make work, but here Black's counterplay is just too fast: }8...cxd4!? 9.exd4 h5! { Wisely ensuring that the  h -file remains closed. Black will now obtain pretty decent counterplay with ... Qb6  or ... Nd7  and already White would do well to accept that things have gone wrong and not continue in direct, aggressive vein: }10.Qd2 Bf5!? 11.O-O-O? Nb4 { Oh dear. Not only is  c2  en prise, but ... Qa5  and ... Rc8  are on their way as it becomes clear that only one side is attacking here, and that it's not White.  Moreover, }{   }8...Qb6 { has also been established as a problem for White, who only really has one good way to deal with the pressure against  d4  and  b2 : }9.Nxc6 bxc6 10.Na4! Qa5+ 11.c3 Nd7! { White may be able to maintain the balance with accuracy, but Black clearly has good play on the dark squares and just what is the pawn doing on  h4 ?   B)  }{   }8.O-O { when the old suggestion of Joe Gallagher's }8...Bf5!? { remains as problematic for White in 2023 as it did back in 1996. White players have tried a great number of moves here, but without really managing to challenge Black. For example, }9.dxc5 Qa5 10.Nb5?! { (G.Smith-Nunn, British Senior Championship, Llandudno 2017) }10...Ne4! 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.Nd4 Qxc5 13.Nxf5 gxf5 { , the f-pawns might be doubled, but Black is slightly for choice with two well-placed minor pieces and }...e5 { on the way. We will certainly aim to avoid such passive positions as White.  In another game, Nunn went for }{   }8...cxd4 9.exd4 { Now }9...Bf5! { is still a decent move and probably a better choice than the tempting double attack on  b2  and  d4 . }10.Nxc6 bxc6 11.Be5 Ne4! { This liquidating leap gave Black easy equality in Tomczak-Nunn, German Bundesliga 1999. Instead, }{   }9...Qb6 10.Nxc6! bxc6 11.Na4! Qa5 12.c3 { and White's grip on the  c5 -square gave him a pleasant edge which he went on to convert in Hebden-Nunn, Hastings 1996/97 (Black also suffered from here in a surprising number of subsequent games). White simply wants to drive the black queen backwards with  b2 - b4  then improve his pieces with  Qd2 ,  Rfe1  and  Bh6 .  The queen recapture }10...Qxc6 { was widely touted as an improvement after the first Hebden-Nunn game. Richard landed up with experience of the move on both sides of the board. Black is very solid, but White can aim to make something of the slightly more active pieces and grip on the  e5 -square: }11.a4! Bf5 12.Bb5 Qc8 13.Re1 a6 14.Bf1 { White's position was slightly the more pleasant in Palliser-S.Franklin, Long Buckby (Yorkshire vs Surrey) 2017. White would like to clamp down on the queenside with  a4 - a5  and  Na4 , and may also take control of  e4  with  f2 - f3 . } )
8. exd4
8. Nfd7{ Challenging for control of the key  e5 -square. }( 8...Qb6!? 9.Na4 Qa5+ 10.c3 Nfd7 { Black should be fine here, since while White can expand with  b2 - b4  that will also create targets for the opponent's counterplay. } )( {   }9.Qd2!? { can lead to fascinating gambit play, but unfortunately for White, Black can't also decline: }9...Nc6 10.Nxc6 bxc6 11.Na4 Qd8 { With ... Nd7  or ... Ne4  next up, Black should be able to acquire sufficient counterplay. } )
9. Nf3{ Best. It may not be what White wants to play, but improvements aren't at all easy to come by. }( 9.Qd2?! Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Bxe5 11.dxe5 d4 { With ...  Qd5  and/or ... Nc6  on the way, the  e5 -pawn is in trouble and White already worse. } )
9. Nf6
10. Ne5
10. Nfd7
11. Nf3
11. Nf6
12. Qd2{ Playing for the win, with Hebden admitting after the game that he 'was just teasing him' by first including a couple of repetitions. }( 12.O-O Nc6 13.Ne5 Bf5 { As we saw above, with the move count four moves lower, Black should be fine here, being set to go ... Rc8  and/or ... Nd7 . } )
12. Bg4
13. Ne5{ Back again as Hebden makes his favourite knight leap for a third time in the game. }
13. Bxe2
14. Qxe2
14. Nh5{ A rather provocative choice, encouraging White to go long and push the kingside pawns. }( 14...Nc6 15.O-O-O Rc8 { Black should have enough counterplay here, with ... Qa5  and ... Nb4  the plan, and always the option of meeting  h2 - h4  with ... h5  if needed. } )
15. Be3
15. Nc6
16. O-O-O{ Everything is now set for kingside expansion as Hebden rightly doesn't fear an exchange on  e5 . }
16. Rc8( 16...Nxe5? 17.dxe5 Bxe5 18.Nxd5 { Thanks to the threats of  Nf6 + and  g2 - g4 , as well as the pressure against  e7 , White has seized a strong early initiative. } )
17. f4( 17.g4!? Nf6 18.f3 { This calmer and more common attacking structure, intending  h4 - h5 , was probably also a better one. } )
17. Nf6
18. g4
18. Qa5( 18...e6! { This would have been a good prophylactic advance. Black is now set to, say, go ... Na5 - c4  and meanwhile wants to lure White forwards: }19.h4 h5! { Unfortunately for White, there just isn't an especially dangerous approach here, since Black always has a timely ... Ne7 , as well as ... Qa5 . }20.gxh5 Nxh5 21.Rdg1 Ne7 { Black is slightly for choice with  g6  secure and even a certain exchange sacrifice now a possibility White must consider. } )
19. a3{ An important advance. We're taught not to move pawns in front of the king in such race scenarios, but here White absolutely had to cut out the powerful concept of ... Nb4  followed by an exchange sacrifice on  c3 . }
19. Nxe5( 19...a6 20.Kb1 e6! { With  d5  secure, Black would have been all set to go ... b5 . The position is fairly sharp, but also roughly level. For example: }21.h4 b5 22.Bd2! 22...b4!? 23.Nxc6 Rxc6 24.axb4 Qb6! 25.f5 Rb8 { and absolutely anything might happen (or '-0.06' in engine speak). } )
20. fxe5
20. Rxc3{ A standard enough attacking mechanism, but Nunn has miscalculated. }( 20...Nd7! 21.Rd3! Nb6 22.h4 { The position is still quite sharp, but White appears slightly for choice since his attack will be pretty quick once he's got in  h4 - h5 . } )
21. exf6
21. Rfc8
22. Kb1{ Nunn had overlooked this cool, calm intermezzo. }( 22.bxc3?? Qxa3+ 23.Kb1 Rc6 24.Qb5 exf6 { Black will regain his material with some advantage. } )( 22.fxg7? Rxa3! 23.bxa3 Qxa3+ 24.Kd2 Qa5+ 25.Kc1 Qa3+ 26.Kb1 Qb4+ { is perpetual check. } )
22. Rxc2( 22...Bxf6 23.bxc3 Qxa3 24.Bc1 { As there's always a timely  c3 - c4  push, White should be able to defend easily enough on the queenside then exploit his extra rook. } )( 22...Qb6!? 23.fxg7 Rxc2 24.Qxc2 Rxc2 25.Kxc2 { White's two rooks and bishop should gradually overpower the black queen, but it's still a bit surprising that Nunn didn't find this only real path to mount some resistance. } )
23. Rd2( { Black is losing material as }23...Rxd2 24.Bxd2 { attacks  a5  and  g7 , so had to call it a day. A crushing victory for the Barry and one which made a teenage Richard sit up, take notice and want to play the opening and  7.Ne5 . } )
