7. dxc5{ The little twist that we'll be recommending in  Chapter Two.  Perhaps it doesn't seem such a surprising move to you and the capture has been around for a long time, but in the field of club chess, especially in the UK, it should spring a surprise, White usually opting for a  Ne5  and likely  O-O  approach. }
7. Qa5{ The obvious response and most common approach, threatening ... Ne4  and thereby regaining the pawn. }( 7...Nbd7!? { Black can also play to regain his pawn this way when we recommend that White is brave and takes up the challenge: }8.Nxd5! Nxd5 9.Qxd5 { All will be revealed in  chapter 2B  including a fairly promising looking exchange sacrifice. } )
8. Nd2{ Taking control of  e4  and even threatening to retain the extra pawn with  Nb3  lest Black now does anything lax. }
8. Qxc5
9. Nb3{ The knight reappears and with the two knights now stationed next to each other, the one on  c3  no longer appears slightly out on a limb. }
9. Qb6
10. Bf3{ Increasing the pressure against  d5 , a pawn White just must ensure he doesn't swap  b2  for. }( 10.a4!? { White exploits the presence of the knight-pair on the queenside to seize some useful space and this immediate advance will be our recommendation in  Line 2A  when we tackle the main line with  6...c5 . } )
10. Rd8( 10...Be6 { Black can also defend  d5  like this and did so in a battle between two leading Barry Attack experts, Blatny-Okhotnik, Austrian League 2012: }11.a4! Nc6?! 12.a5 Qd8 13.O-O { White's position is already the more pleasant. He may go  a5 - a6 , which will either see lines opening faster on that flank than Black would wish, or leave him after ... b6  with a strong advanced unit on  a6 , one which will be quite the asset come an endgame. We should also note the simple and strong plan of  Qe2 ,  Rfd1  and  Qb5 , as well as Black's lack of counterplay. }13...a6 14.Qe2 14...Ne4!? { A radical choice and one which reflects the significant potential pressure Black may well come under down the d-file. }15.Nxe4 dxe4 16.Bxe4 Bxb3?! ( 16...Bxb2 17.Ra4!? { With  Nc5  high on the agenda, White retains the initiative and a pleasant edge. } )17.Rfd1! Qc8 18.cxb3 { This left Blatny a pawn to the good and with the bishop-pair, and he went on to grind out the win. } )( 10...Nc6!? { This is probably Black's best move when White should castle or push the a-pawn, and definitely not grab: }11.Nxd5? Nxd5 12.Bxd5 ( 12.Qxd5 Bxb2 13.Rb1 Bc3+ 14.Kf1 Qa6+ { With the a-pawn falling, the opening has certainly not been a success for White. } )Rd8 13.Qf3 Bxb2 { With both ... Qb4 + and ... Bxa1  threatened, White should most certainly steer clear of this position. } )
11. a4{ Getting back on track as White aims to annoy the black queen or force Black to weaken his queenside. }
11. a5
12. Be5{ White should always be looking to occupy this square when he can, but here doing so appears premature as Black has a tactical solution. }( 12.Nb5? Ne8 { This might be a retreat, but it secures Black an early advantage with either ... Bxb2  or ... e5  next up. } )( 12.Qd4!? { This looks like a better version of Blatny's approach and a decent alternative to simply castling. For example: }12...Qxd4 13.exd4 Nc6 14.O-O-O !? { A bold, but decent approach. White uses the king to help ensure  c2  is secure and would now like to begin to probe with  Rhe1  and  Nb5  followed by  c2 - c3 . } )
12. e6{ Returning the small favour. }( 12...Nbd7! { This either makes the bishop drop back to  g3 , when Black would be fairly comfortably placed, or White enter a slightly hairy line: }13.Nxd5!? Nxd5 14.Bxg7 Nxe3! { This would be very bad news for White, but for a resource: }15.Bd4! Qb4+!? 16.c3 Qxd4! 17.Qxd4 Nc2+ 18.Ke2 Nxd4+ 19.cxd4 Nf6 { With ... Be6 - d5  on the way, Black is even arguably slightly for choice in this resulting endgame. } )
13. Bd4{ Continuing to discombobulate as the Czech Grandmaster has realised that Black's most natural looking move is far from a good one. }
13. Qc7( 13...Qd6? 14.Nb5 Qe7 15.Bc5 { Here too Black finds himself in serious early trouble, since  Bb6  followed by  Nc7  will pick off an exchange. } )( 13...Qc6 14.g4!? { By no means obligatory, but this is a tempting way to exploit White's lead in development and the fact that he hasn't yet castled: }14...Nbd7 15.g5 Ne8 16.h4 { White has seized the initiative and may yet get to enjoy a promising attack after  h4 - h5 . Note that the king can still go to the queenside, as well as that Black isn't yet in a position to push ... e5  due to the weakness of  d5 . } )( 13...Qb4!? 14.Bc5 Qh4 { This also feels a bit risky for Black with the queen arguably misplaced on  h4 , but White may not have anything better than castling with a pleasant enough setup, as going after  a5  is not so simple: }15.Bb6 Rd6 16.Bxa5?! Ne8! { Black prevents the bishop escaping via  c7  and will now obtain powerful counterplay with ... Rda6 . } )
14. Nb5{ Expanding with tempo and only leaving the black queen with one way of staying in touch with the  b6 -square. }
14. Qc6( 14...Qe7 15.Bc5! Qd7 16.Bb6 { As we've already noted, White will win the exchange on  d8  or via  Nc7 . } )
15. c4{ A highly tempting advance, aiming to make maximum use of White's lead in development and significantly more active pieces. }( 15.Rc1! { Preparing the  c2 - c4  advance so would have been even stronger, which makes sense once you try to find a decent move for Black here. } )
15. Qxc4{ Good defence from Schmidt, making White justify his play, not just easily get to crash through with  cxd5  and  Rc1 . }
16. Nd2
16. Qc6{ But this undoes all the good work of the previous turn and lets White in down the  c -file after all. }( 16...Qb4! 17.Nc7 Ra6 18.Nxa6 Nxa6 19.O-O { Black doesn't have enough for the exchange, but is clearly very much still on the board. For his part, White should look to play down the  c -file and might also consider regrouping while maintaining control of  e5  with  Be2  and  f2 - f4 . } )
17. Rc1
17. Qd7
18. Nc7{ Simple chess, collecting the exchange. }
18. Ra6
19. Nxa6
19. Nxa6
20. Bb6( { Resignation may seem slightly premature and yet consider: }20...Nb4!? 21.O-O! Re8 22.Bxa5 Nc6 23.Bb6 { White is a clear exchange to the good and may increase the pressure with  Be2 - b5  or simply  Bc5  and  b2 - b4 . } )
