5. Nb5( { A change of approach from }5.e3 { . This queenside raid has been fairly topical in recent years and might well still catch out non-GM opponents. White moves the knight for a second time, but has a certain threat and forces Black's own queen's knight to move to the rim. While our main coverage is devoted to the main line, }5.e3 { , we will also take a look at }5.Nb5 { in Chapter 5 lest you want to add a second string to your Barry bow. } )
5. Na6
6. h3( { Even a well-prepared opponent may be slightly surprised by this modest move, but it's far from a bad one. }6.e3 { has been somewhat more common and can easily transpose after a subsequent  h2 - h3 , but there's nothing wrong with taking control of the  g4 -square and also giving the Barry bishop a retreat square. After }6.e3 { Black might consider }6...Nh5!? { . } )( { In contrast, }6.h3 Nh5?! 7.Bh2 { would achieve little for Black bar to leave both knights on the rim. } )
6. O-O{ The Argentinean Grandmaster is happy with conventional development. But what if Black pushes the knight away? }( 6...c6!? 7.Na3! { The unusual moves continue, but this way White avoids allowing Black an improved version of our main game with 7.  Nc3   Ne4 !. The knight also isn't so badly placed on  a3 , supporting, once White has completed kingside development, both the  c2 - c4  break and even a  b2 - b4 - b5  advance, most likely after first  c2 - c3 . Let's see how play might continue: }7...O-O 8.e3 { and now:   A)  8... c5  9.c3  b6 ?! 10.Nb5! }{ A powerful return of the knight. Why now? Well, White prevents Black from regrouping with ... Na6 - b8 - c6  and also intends to advance with  a2 - a4 , thereby obtaining a handy clamp on the queenside, one also known to be quite useful for the first player in the Jobava London.   B)  }{   }8...Nc7 9.Bd3 Nce8 10.O-O { Calmly completing kingside development. Now White may look to the  c2 - c4  break or even regroup with  Na3 - b1 - d2  if you prefer. Don't forget that Black too has lost plenty of time with the queen's knight. }10...Nd6 { This was a fourth move with the same piece in Micic-Pacan-Milej, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2023, and here White might well have continued to annoy the black knight: }11.c4! { This thematic advance gives White a pleasant edge. Black would rather not exchange on  c4  and bring the white knight back into the game, but otherwise White may simply improve with  Rc1  or even go  c4 - c5  followed by  b2 - b4 . } )
7. e3{ It's finally time to create a path into the game for the king's bishop. }
7. Ne4{ White's unstereotyped play with  5.Nb5  often encourages Black to try and do something active quite early on, but such play rarely troubles White, who isn't exactly miles behind in development and also enjoys a pretty solid, London-type setup. }
8. Nd2{ The strong Vietnamese Grandmaster wastes no time in challenging Black's piece and acting before Black gets any aggressive ideas of expansion with ... f6  and ...  e5 . }
8. Nxd2
9. Qxd2{ The position may not look like too much for White, but there are definitely reasons to be happy. Observe Black's lack of active play and also what is that knight doing on  a6 ? Yes, it can regroup via  b8  or  c7 , but doing so will lose time and may still fail to deliver Black the activity he desires. }
9. c6( 9...c5 { This might appear more active, but now the black knight is rather stranded on  a6  and White doesn't even need to push  c2 - c3  in response: }10.Be2!? Bd7 11.a4! { Obtaining the aforementioned strong queenside bind. }11...Qb6!? 12.Bh2!? { This might be the critical line. White's retreat might look a little mysterious, but there's a point to this prophylactic play: }12...Bxb5 13.axb5 Nc7?! 14.Qa5! { Now that ... Ne6  doesn't hit a bishop on  f4 , this is a strong activation of the queen. }14...Ne6 15.c3 { Securing  d4  leaves White clearly for choice with Black's knight still short of a good square and White all set to castle then perhaps double rooks on the a-file.  Matters now quickly went wrong for Black in one high-profile blitz encounter after }{   }11...Bc6 12.O-O Qd7 13.c3 { This left the knight on  a6  misplaced and Black also tied down to the defence of  a7 , meaning that White enjoyed an extremely pleasant edge in Carlsen-Vachier Lagrave, SpeedChess 2022, where matters quickly became even more unpleasant for Black: }13...c4?! 14.e4! dxe4 ( { (Or }14...Bxb5?! 15.axb5 Qxb5 16.exd5 Qxd5 17.Rfe1 Rfe8 18.Qc2 { Black's extra pawn is surely but temporary, as White can always attack  c4 , as well as simply go  Bf3  and  Qe4 , while also rather dominating the board. }{ ) } )15.Bxc4 e5!? 16.dxe5! { Simple chess. Removing the queens ensures that Black should continue to struggle for counterplay for quite some time. }16...Qxd2 17.Bxd2 Bxe5 18.Be3 { Not only was  a7  vulnerable, but White could increase the pressure with  a4 - a5  and  Rfd1 . The only surprise is that for once Carlsen didn't manage to convert this clear advantage. } )
10. Nc3{ The knight heads back from where it came, which is a good policy when there's no ... Ne4  in response and here Le Quang Liem also has quite an aggressive follow-up in mind. }
10. b6{ This may seem natural enough, but is rather slow and Black should likely prioritise improving his knight from the rim, as we'll see in  chapter 5C.  }
11. h4{ Le Quang Liem is fully aware that the early exchange of knights has robbed the black king of one of it's main defenders and with Black hardly up to much, why not just go for it on the kingside? White seizes the initiative and advantage with this powerful advance. If allowed, he'd like to go  h4 - h5 , then  O-O-O ,  e3 - e4 ,  Bh6  and deliver mate down the  h -file. }
11. h5{ Perez Ponsa understandably would like to keep lines closed on the kingside. }
12. O-O-O( 12.Be2! { Preparing  g2 - g4  so was probably even stronger as the white king is safe enough on  e1  for now. } )( 12.g4!? { Even this was possible, exploiting the fact that Black's bishop must stay on  c8  to defend his knight. }12...hxg4 13.h5 { White simply wants to exchange on  g6  then go  Bd3  and  O-O-O  and, with the safer king, must enjoy decent play for the pawn. } )
12. Nc7( 12...b5! { This logical advance might have made White wish he'd not been in such a rush to house the king. After }13.f3 b4 14.Na4 Qa5 15.b3 c5! { , with both ... Bd7  and ... c4  on their way, Black must have enough counterplay.  Better is }{   }13.Ne2!? b4 14.f3 c5! 15.g4!? { . White may be slightly for choice here, but with both sides clearly largely all in, absolutely anything might happen in an actual game. } )
13. Be2
13. Re8{ Perez Ponsa knows the dictum about flank attacks being best met by central action, but surely this move is too slow here? }
14. e4{ This fast rapid game begins to veer out of control. }( 14.Rdg1! { This direct move would have placed the black king fully in White's sights and simply left him doing very well. For example: }14...e5 15.Bxe5 Bxe5 16.dxe5 Rxe5 17.f4! Re8 18.g4 { Blasting open lines with some effect towards the beleaguered monarch. } )
14. b5( 14...dxe4! { and if }15.Nxe4 Bf5 { Black seems to have enough counterplay here, with an immediate central threat and also the possibility of ... Ne6 , attacking  d4 , then maybe going ... c5 .  White can try }{   }15.g4!? hxg4 16.h5 e5! { . By now, the central response would appear to have arrived in time and Black is surely OK here. } )
15. Bf3( 15.e5! { With  f2 - f3  and  g2 - g4  high on the agenda, as well as ideas of a timely  Bh6 , White would again have been doing pretty well had he logically closed the centre so. } )
15. b4
16. Na4
16. dxe4( 16...Ne6!? { This might have been even stronger, especially as it's far from easy for White to maintain control here. He can preserve the key dark-squared bishop, but not obtain anything more than a mess: }17.Bh6 Bxd4 18.exd5 cxd5 19.Qxb4 a5 { It's once again far from clear which king is the more vulnerable. } )
17. Bxe4
17. Nd5
18. Bh6{ Preserving the bishop for now and hoping to eliminate its counterpart. }
18. Qa5( 18...Bf6! { This was arguably not such an easy move to blitz out, but would have retained an important piece and been fine for Black, who still has ideas of both ... Qa5  and ... e5 . } )
19. Bxg7
19. Kxg7
20. b3{ Calm and good defence, refusing to panic on the queenside. }( 20.Bxd5?! cxd5! 21.b3 Bf5 { The weakness of  c2  and fact Black can still break with ... e5  leaves White on the back foot. } )
20. Ba6{ An obvious follow-up, as well as one which isn't immediately punished. }
21. Kb2{ To secure  a2 , but there was much better. }( 21.g4! { The kingside attack roars back into life to leave White at least clearly for choice. }21...hxg4? 22.h5 { With the white queen set to land on  g5  or even  h6 , Black is in big trouble. } )
21. Bb5
22. Bxd5{ A simple positional refutation of Black's rather one-dimensional play. }
22. cxd5
23. Nc5{ This is ever a fine outpost for the knight in the Barry once Black can no longer challenge the  c5 -square with the  b -pawn. }
23. Qa3+
24. Kb1
24. a5{ Desperately trying to obtain an attack on the white king after all, but Le Quang Liem's next scotches the notion that someone other than White can attack here. }
25. Rh3
25. Kh7( 25...a4? 26.bxa4 { White is simply winning material. } )
26. Re1
26. Rac8
27. Qf4
27. Kg8
28. Rf3
