1. d4
1. d5( 1...Nf6 2.Nf3 g6 3.Nc3 d5 4.Bf4 Bg7 5.e3 O-O 6.Be2 { would, of course, be our standard route into the game. } )
2. Bf4{ Yes, the London can transpose into the Barry on the odd occasion! }
2. Nf6
3. e3
3. g6
4. Nf3
4. Bg7
5. Be2
5. O-O
6. Nc3{ Not for the famous and highly creative Dutch IM the normal London moves, such as  h2 - h3  or  c2 - c3 , but rather something more aggressive - a transposition into the Barry Attack. }
6. c6
7. h4{ A bold advance and one we took a good look at in the realm of  chapter 1C...  }
7. Bg4
8. Ne5( { ...But after this thematic leap, we're about to return to the realm of  chapter 1B,   which explores   }6...Bg4 7.Ne5 { . } )
8. Bxe2
9. Qxe2
9. Nbd7{ Black's setup is quite solid and reasonably common, but it's actually far from easy for him to acquire decent counterplay. }
10. O-O-O{ Housing the king and connecting the rooks ahead of operations on the kingside. }
10. Nxe5( 10...Rc8!? 11.Kb1 c5 { At least this obtains some counterplay, although White has sufficient control not to be too concerned. }12.Qf3!? { We saw this policy of prudently covering against an exchange sacrifice on  c3  while preparing to swing the queen to the  h -file in  chapter 1B.  } )
11. Bxe5{ The best choice here, even with Black's knight on  f6 . }( 11.dxe5?! Nd7 12.e4 e6 { Suddenly, the position is far from clear and there's just no need to unbalance the position so and allow Black some play. } )
11. Qc8
