13. c5{ A natural enough move, but it transpires that Bjerke's concept will be too slow to trouble White. In any case though, Black's position is already somewhat unpleasant. }( 13...Ne8 { This had been tried in an earlier game, but is far from a panacea for Black. }14.Bxg7 Nxg7 15.e4 { With central domination, as well as the strong concept of  h4 - h5  in conjunction with  Qe3 , White could be delighted with the outcome of the opening in Ansell-Blasko, Winterthur 2009. } )( 13...h6!? { A common enough method for trying to keep lines relatively closed in such positions. Black will meet }14.g5 { with }14...Nh5 { and }14.h5 { with }14...g5 { . The trick as White is usually not to panic and not to rush those advances.  For example, a switch to central play with }{   }14.Rhe1 { followed by  Kb1  and  e3 - e4  also makes a good deal of sense, although here White can very much be direct with }14.Rdg1! b5 15.g5 { White wastes no time blasting open lines and will likely bring up the reserves from  f3  to strengthen the attack. Here, }15...hxg5?! 16.Rxg5!? { breaks up White's pawn skeleton, but it's all about opening lines. Now  f3 - f4  or  h4 - h5  will follow - with some force. }16...Nh7 17.Rg2 Bxe5 { Black might as well have a pawn for his suffering. }18.dxe5 Qxe5 19.f4 { With  h4 - h5  next up, White enjoys far more than enough for the sacrificed pawn. He may strengthen the attack with  Qf3 - h3  and even involve the knight, via  e2  and then  d4  or  g3 .  Alternatively, Black can try }{   }15...Nh5 16.Bxg7 { Going for maximum disruption, although a very good case can be made too for calmly seizing space with  f3 - f4 . }16...Kxg7 17.gxh6+!? Kxh6 18.Rg5 { White remains clearly for choice, despite Black's fairly decent defensive play. Now  f3 - f4 - f5  is the plan, all the while aiming to force a weakening ... f6 , after which White will be quick to pile up against the  g6 -pawn. Note too that the knight may yet join in the attack or at least influence proceedings with some effect, from  c5  in the event of ... b4 ;  Na4 , or via  e2  and  g3  or even  d1 - f2 - g4 . } )
14. h5
14. c4
15. Qh2{ A dream attacking position, with very heavy pressure down the  h -file towards the enemy king. }
15. h6{ As good a defensive try as anything, as Bjerke strives to keep the  h -file closed. }( 15...b5?! 16.Nxb5 { Thank you very much, says White, safely pocketing a pawn thanks to controlling the  b8 -square. } )( 15...a6!? 16.hxg6 fxg6 17.f4! { This seems even stronger than pushing the  e -pawn. White wants to crash through with  f4 - f5 . }( { ( }17.Bxf6? Rxf6 18.Qxh7+? Kf7 { would be a case of prematurely cashing in on the kingside. White does want to remove the knight from  f6 , but not at the expense of his dark-squared bishop, unless exchanging so forces mate. }{ ) } )17...Qxg4 18.Nxd5! { A classic overloading sacrifice to break though. }18...Nxd5 19.Qxh7+ { It's not quite mate, but matters are clearly terminal for Black with his bishop falling and also  Rdg1  imminent. } )
