2. d6
3. Nc3{ Even against Black's Old Indian  2...d6  move order, Barry-like play works well as White prepares to expand in the centre with  e2 - e4 . }
3. Bf5
4. Bg5{ Planning to break up Black's pawns if allowed, followed by  e2 - e4 , although the pawn may also be quite happy to simply step up just to  e3 , thereby facilitating  Bd3  to fight against Black's most active piece on  f5 . }
4. Nbd7
5. Nh4( { Hunting down the bishop pair, since now both both }5...Be4 6.f3 { and }5...Bg4?! 6.h3 Bh5 7.g4 { only help White to expand with tempo. } )
5. Bg6
6. Nxg6
6. hxg6
7. d5{ A strong, cramping advance. White will now meet any advance of the black  e -pawn with an exchange on  e6 , leaving some rather large gashes in the black kingside. Meanwhile,  e2 - e4  is on the way, and White enjoys a pleasant edge with the bishop pair and extra space. }
