1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3{ The hearts of many King's Indian and Grünfeld players sink when they see this, knowing that they won't be about to face the main lines of their respective favourite openings. This repertoire is all about denying such players the dynamic fun they crave while fighting for the initiative as White from an early stage. }
2. g6
3. Nc3{ The move that introduces the Barry Attack as White prepares to take over the centre without delay. }
3. d5{ Black's main move, fighting for control of  e4 , as well as the most popular choice by some margin, although at lower levels, plenty of even non-Pirc players neglect to make this advance, perhaps being too keen on remaining within a King's Indian setup. }
4. Bf4{ The second key move which constitutes the Barry Attack. White places the bishop on a fairly aggressive square and on a diagonal Black can no longer obstruct with ... d6 . White may now follow up by attacking  c7  with  Nb5  or simply continue development with  e2 - e3  and  Be2 . }
4. Bg7
5. Nb5{ As a secondary option, we've also  covered  this fashionable line which is likely to surprise opponents at club level. The direct attack on  c7  pretty much forces Black's hand. }
5. Na6( 5...O-O? 6.Bxc7! { Simply winning a clear pawn and with tempo, and do note too that }6.Nxc7? Nh5 { would be somewhat less effective. } )
6. h3{ We quite like this immediate prophylactic advance, one which once again takes ideas of ... Bg4  and ... Nh5  off the table. }
6. O-O
7. e3{ Positional play is the order of the day in the modern Barry and here White sensibly prepares to complete development with  Be2  and  O-O . }
7. c5
8. c3{ Securing  d4  and now White will play for a queenside clamp with  a2 - a4 . }
8. Bd7
9. a4{ A strong advance, as we'll see further in  Chapter 5A.  It's not hard to imagine plenty of club and internet players stumbling into this position as Black, then struggling to free their pieces. The knight on  b5  is very strong, and ... Bxb5 ;  axb5  is unlikely to help Black, but how else to free the  a6 -knight and the  a8 -rook for action? }
9. c4
10. b3{ A key break in general against ... c4  and a decent choice here, fighting back immediately on the queenside. }
10. cxb3
11. Qxb3{ The knight on  b5  continues to exert a strong influence over the position, and White is now all set to complete development with  Be2  and  O-O , after which he may be able to look towards such active ideas as  Ne5  and/or  c3 - c4 . }
