4. Bg7
5. e3{ Our main recommendation, simply intending  Be2  and then  Ne5  and  h2 - h4 - h5 , if allowed. }
5. O-O
6. Be2{ Completing minor piece development, and all is now set for  Ne5  and  h2 - h4 , launching an early attack. }
6. b6
7. Ne5{ The leap is especially justified against Black's rather slow attempt at setting up a double fianchetto. White simply wants to power ahead with  h2 - h4 - h5 . }
7. Bb7( { If }7...c5 { , White ignores the queenside demonstration to proceed full-steam ahead on the kingside. }8.h4! Bb7 9.h5 { Already White is all set to open lines with an exchange on  g6 , as well as go  Qd2  and  O-O-O , with promising attacking chances as covered in  the game  Rogers-Su.Polgar, Dortmund 1985. } )
8. h4{ An early attack, but a fairly strong one, as well as an attack made possible by White's firm control of  e5  and Black's lack of early counterplay. }
8. Nbd7
