9. Nxe5
10. Bxe5{ Recapturing with a piece maintains control of  e5  as White refuses to fear early simplification. }
10. Ne4{ At least this way Black won't get swiftly mated. }
11. Bxg7
11. Kxg7
12. Nxe4{ Having eliminated a key defender on  g7 , White creates a dead point on  e4 . }
12. dxe4
13. h6+{ AlphaZeroesque play. With three sets of minor pieces off the board, White was unlikely to be able to force mate down the  h -file, so settles for long-term gains. }
13. Kg8
14. Qd2{ With such a fish bone wedged in his throat, Black's king will never be too comfortable, and they also have the worse structure. Meanwhile, White is all set to complete development by castling long and enjoys a pleasant edge, as we'll see in  Chapter 1A.  }
