1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3{ The hearts of many King's Indian and Grünfeld players sink when they see this, knowing that they won't be about to face the main lines of their respective favourite openings. This repertoire is all about denying such players the dynamic fun they crave while fighting for the initiative as White from an early stage. }
2. g6
3. Nc3{ The move that introduces the Barry Attack as White prepares to take over the centre without delay. }
3. d5{ Black's main move, fighting for control of  e4 , as well as the most popular choice by some margin, although at lower levels, plenty of even non-Pirc players neglect to make this advance, perhaps being too keen on remaining within a King's Indian setup. }
4. Bf4{ The second key move which constitutes the Barry Attack. White places the bishop on a fairly aggressive square and on a diagonal Black can no longer obstruct with ... d6 . White may now follow up by attacking  c7  with  Nb5  or simply continue development with  e2 - e3  and  Be2 . }
4. Bg7
5. e3{ Our main recommendation, simply intending  Be2  and then  Ne5  and  h2 - h4 - h5 , if allowed. }
5. O-O
6. Be2{ Completing minor piece development, and all is now set for  Ne5  and  h2 - h4 , launching an early attack. }
6. c6
7. h4( { Our main recommendation in  Chapter 1C,   pushing the  h -pawn before moving the knight for a specific reason: White wants to bypass Black's idea of }7.Ne5 Nfd7! { , challenging hard for the control of  e5 . } )
7. Nbd7
8. Ne5{ Now that the queen's knight is on  d7 , White can leap forwards in approved fashion. }
8. Nxe5
9. Bxe5{ Our standard recapture and, once again, Black will now either fall under early and unpleasant pressure on the kingside after  h4 - h5  or, more prudently, will seek early exchanges. }
9. Ne4
10. Bxg7{ Removing an important defender and possible as White doesn't have to take on doubled  c -pawns here. }
10. Nxc3
11. Qd3{ This intermezzo is why. }
11. Kxg7
12. Qxc3{ Black is pretty solid, but White can expand not only through  h4 - h5  but also  f2 - f4  (or  f2 - f3 ) and  g2 - g4 , as seen in  the game  Pribyl-Labla, Nuremberg Open 1990. }
