*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Barry Main Line - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Main Line - 6...a6 7.Ne5 b6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4{ The traditional starting point of the Barry Attack. }
4. Bg7( { It's hard to believe that Black has a more natural move than to complete the fianchetto, and yet, an experienced and wily opponent might on occasion prefer something else. We'll consider }4...c6 { in  Chapter Three  and Black's fourth move alternatives in  Chapter Four.  } )
5. e3{ White's traditional and most common interpretation of the Barry, simply preparing to develop the light-squared bishop. }
5. O-O{ Another very natural move from Black and overwhelmingly seen at this stage, although it's not entirely forced as we'll see in  Chapter Four,  where we also look at a couple of unusual fifth moves. }
6. Be2{ The usual post these days for the light-squared bishop, as well as a choice which leaves White all set to go  Ne5  and  h4 - h5  should Black now respond in slow fashion. }( { Opponents who've faced the Barry before or who can remember the theory are likely to respond here with }6...c5 { - an important line we'll tackle in  Chapter Two.  There are three fairly common alternatives which we'll chiefly focus on in this section, namely: } )( { 1A) }6...b6 { . See here.  }( { 1B) }6...Bg4 { . See  here.  }( { 1C) }6...c6 { . See  here.  }( { Of these, the first two do little to curb White's lust for an early kingside attack and direct play is possible too even against the more subtle }6...c6 { . In practice, Black has also tried a great number of somewhat strange and unusual moves, of which a quick examination of the most common four should prove useful lest you're ever surprised at this stage of the Barry. } ) ) ) )
6. a6
7. Ne5{ Our thematic leap. There's no need to fear expansion with ... b5 , while on the kingside White would, of course, like to expand on with  h2 - h4 - h5 . }( { Richard faced the unusual approach }7...Nbd7 { in Palliser-Aguirre, Bradford 2008, where he was happy to increase the pressure with }8.Bf3!? { , but should really have been more direct with }8.h4 { . This echoes how we'll recommend  meeting 6...Nbd7  and here Black has arguably squandered a tempo on ... a6 . As such, he would probably be well advised to rule out any notion of  h4 - h5 : }{    }8...h5 { Here, }9.g4? { doesn't work due to }9...Nxe5 10.dxe5 Nxg4 { .  Therefore, White prepares that advance with }{   }9.f3!? { while also taking control of the  e4 -square.  Qd2  and  O-O-O  may also follow if Black responds in slow fashion, or even  Qd2  and  Nd1 - f2 , rerouting the knight into the attack and offering additional support to the  g2 - g4  break. } )
7. b6{ This rather mixes systems and simply gives Black a tempo-down version of  Chapter 1A.  Still, there may be the occasional opponent even in 2023 who goes  6...a6  }{ solely to cut out  Nb5  possibilities. White should, of course, respond by advancing the  h -pawn. }
8. h4
8. c5
9. h5{ Model play from White, who already enjoys some initiative and advantage. Now you might expect  Qd2  and  O-O-O  to follow, but with Black's queen's knight still at home, White may do even better to increase the pressure against  d5  with  Bf3 . }
9. Be6
10. Bf3{ White may now follow up with  Qe2  and  O-O-O , the  g -pawn is also ready to hurl into the fray and there may even be the option of a timely exchange on  c5  to deny Black any real counterplay. }
10. b5
11. hxg6{ Forcing Black into a fairly big decision on the kingside before capturing on  c5  in any case. }
11. fxg6
12. dxc5
12. Qa5
13. O-O{ A notable change of approach. The king is much safer here than on  c1 . White now threatens  Nxd5 , can always increase the pressure with  Qd4  and  Rad1 , and went on to win in just a further eight moves in Hodgson-Komljenovic, Seville 1987. }
