8. b4
9. Na4{ The knight eyes a fine outpost on  c5  and now  Qd2  will always come with tempo. With Black also low on counterplay, White is already clearly for choice. }
9. Ne4
10. f3
10. Nd6
11. h5{ Pressing ahead on the kingside having naturally driven Black's knight away from  e4 . }
11. g5
12. h6( { While sacrificing a piece with }12.Bxg5!? f6 13.h6 { is tempting, there's just no need to when White can make this powerful advance. It does slow down the attack, but now there's a big hook on  g5  and one which can no longer be supported by ... h6 . } )
12. Bf6
13. Bg3{ This left White in full control in Lucas-Van de Wynkele, Vlissingen 2002, with the simple plan of  Bd3 ,  Qd2  and  O-O-O . White may look to the  e3 - e4  break, although we would probably prefer a plan involving  f3 - f4 , possibly after first  Bf2  and  g2 - g4 , thereby aiming to obtain some pressure against the weakened black kingside after all. }
