6. Be2{ The usual post these days for the light-squared bishop, as well as a choice which leaves White all set to go  Ne5  and  h4 - h5  should Black now respond in slow fashion. }( { Opponents who've faced the Barry before or who can remember the theory are likely to respond here with }6...c5 { - an important line we'll tackle in  Chapter Two.  There are three fairly common alternatives which we'll chiefly focus on in this section, namely: } )( { 1A) }6...b6 { . See here.  }( { 1B) }6...Bg4 { . See  here.  }( { 1C) }6...c6 { . See  here.  }( { Of these, the first two do little to curb White's lust for an early kingside attack and direct play is possible too even against the more subtle }6...c6 { . In practice, Black has also tried a great number of somewhat strange and unusual moves, of which a quick examination of the most common four should prove useful lest you're ever surprised at this stage of the Barry. } ) ) ) )
6. a6
7. Ne5{ Our thematic leap. There's no need to fear expansion with ... b5 , while on the kingside White would, of course, like to expand on with  h2 - h4 - h5 . }( { Richard faced the unusual approach }7...Nbd7 { in Palliser-Aguirre, Bradford 2008, where he was happy to increase the pressure with }8.Bf3!? { , but should really have been more direct with }8.h4 { . This echoes how we'll recommend  meeting 6...Nbd7  and here Black has arguably squandered a tempo on ... a6 . As such, he would probably be well advised to rule out any notion of  h4 - h5 : }{    }8...h5 { Here, }9.g4? { doesn't work due to }9...Nxe5 10.dxe5 Nxg4 { .  Therefore, White prepares that advance with }{   }9.f3!? { while also taking control of the  e4 -square.  Qd2  and  O-O-O  may also follow if Black responds in slow fashion, or even  Qd2  and  Nd1 - f2 , rerouting the knight into the attack and offering additional support to the  g2 - g4  break. } )
7. b5
8. h4( { A bold, fearless and strong advance as it transpires there's no need for White to respond on the queenside with }8.a3 { or }8.a4!? { . Instead,  h4 - h5  is again introduced to the agenda and Black might well elect to try and keep lines closed on the kingside. } )
8. h5
9. Bf3( { A useful move to flick in here. White hopes to force Black to either move something to  e6  as }9...Nbd7? { would just allow }10.Nxd5 { , or weaken the queenside with   }9...b4?! 10.Na4 { . } )
9. Be6
10. g4{ Boom! Why not this push when White controls the  g4 -square? }
10. hxg4
11. Nxg4
11. Nxg4
12. Bxg4( { With Black's bishop still on  c8 , matters wouldn't be so clear after  ...c5 , but here White threatens }12...-- 13.Bxe6 fxe6 14.Qg4 { as well as, of course,  h4 - h5 . } )
12. Qd7
13. Bxe6
13. Qxe6
14. h5{ White is well ahead in any attacking race and will be quick to increase the pressure after  Qf3  and  O-O-O . }
