[White "1) Barry Main Line - 6th Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Main Line - 6...Nh5 7.Bg5 h6 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4{ The traditional starting point of the Barry Attack. }
4. Bg7( { It's hard to believe that Black has a more natural move than to complete the fianchetto, and yet, an experienced and wily opponent might on occasion prefer something else. We'll consider }4...c6 { in  Chapter Three  and Black's fourth move alternatives in  Chapter Four.  } )
5. e3{ White's traditional and most common interpretation of the Barry, simply preparing to develop the light-squared bishop. }
5. O-O{ Another very natural move from Black and overwhelmingly seen at this stage, although it's not entirely forced as we'll see in  Chapter Four,  where we also look at a couple of unusual fifth moves. }
6. Be2{ The usual post these days for the light-squared bishop, as well as a choice which leaves White all set to go  Ne5  and  h4 - h5  should Black now respond in slow fashion. }( { Opponents who've faced the Barry before or who can remember the theory are likely to respond here with }6...c5 { - an important line we'll tackle in  Chapter Two.  There are three fairly common alternatives which we'll chiefly focus on in this section, namely: } )( { 1A) }6...b6 { . See here.  }( { 1B) }6...Bg4 { . See  here.  }( { 1C) }6...c6 { . See  here.  }( { Of these, the first two do little to curb White's lust for an early kingside attack and direct play is possible too even against the more subtle }6...c6 { . In practice, Black has also tried a great number of somewhat strange and unusual moves, of which a quick examination of the most common four should prove useful lest you're ever surprised at this stage of the Barry. } ) ) ) )
6. Nh5
7. Bg5( { Needless to say, unlike }7.Be5 f6! { , we retain an important bishop against Black's rather ambitious idea. } )
7. h6
8. Bh4
8. g5
9. g4( { White has scored well enough in practice with }9.Ne5 { , but Richard was delighted to see that the modern-day engines approve of both his old idea of taking the fight to Black on the kingside and even the next few moves of his old analysis. } )
9. gxh4
10. gxh5{ White isn't so much interested in taking on  h4 , as mobilising the troops with  Rg1 ,  Qd2  or even  Qd3 , and  O-O-O . }
10. Bg4
11. Ne5{ The thematic leap. Now  f2 - f4  may follow, as well as  Rg1 , and Black is all set to come under pressure. }
