8. h4{ Even against Black's best seventh move, one which at least helps him obtain a bit of play, White should proceed straight ahead and now  9.h5  will follow if allowed. }
8. Bb7
9. h5( { Already White is all set to ask something of an awkward question on }g6 { . For example, }9...e6 10.hxg6 fxg6 11.Qd2 { is simple chess, preparing to go long now that the  h -file isn't fully open. }11...Nbd7 12.O-O-O a6 13.Rh3!? { simply intending  Rdh1  followed by  Bg5  and a 2500+ rated played failed to survive as Black in Callens-Sande, correspondence 1999. } )
9. Nbd7
10. hxg6{ This exchange is rarely a bad policy and may give White extra options beyond  Qd2  and  O-O-O . }
10. hxg6
