1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. b6( { Black aims for a double fianchetto, an approach which is too slow against the Barry, as we noted in  the game  Rogers-Polgar. White should certainly be quite happy when }6...b6 { appears on the board and while it's long since fallen out of favour amongst grandmasters, at sub-2300 level the move is still quite common, which may suggest that the Barry Attack still carries a certain surprise value in 2023. } )
7. Ne5{ Our favourite leap (bar when  Black plays 6... c5 ! ), and now everything is set for the  h -pawn to hurtle down the board. }
7. c5
8. h4{ Even against Black's best seventh move, one which at least helps him obtain a bit of play, White should proceed straight ahead and now  9.h5  will follow if allowed. }
8. Bb7
9. h5( { Already White is all set to ask something of an awkward question on }g6 { . For example, }9...e6 10.hxg6 fxg6 11.Qd2 { is simple chess, preparing to go long now that the  h -file isn't fully open. }11...Nbd7 12.O-O-O a6 13.Rh3!? { simply intending  Rdh1  followed by  Bg5  and a 2500+ rated played failed to survive as Black in Callens-Sande, correspondence 1999. } )
9. Nc6
10. hxg6
10. fxg6
11. Qd2( { A stronger choice than the }11.Bb5 { of Rogers-Polgar, Dortmund 1985 (see  here ), well though that quickly turned out. There we'll see that }11...Ne4? 12.Nxe4 dxe4 13.Bc4+ { would already be a disaster on the light squares for Black, and in any case he's already in some trouble with  O-O-O  on the way. } )
11. e6
12. O-O-O
12. Qe7
13. Bg5{ White wants to obtain a powerful central grip after  f2-f4  then swing the queen into the attack via  e1  and  h4 . }( { This modest little move is even better than the }13.Rh2 { of Welling-Bezler, Schaan 1999. } )
