5. O-O
6. Be2
6. b6( { Black aims for a double fianchetto, an approach which is too slow against the Barry, as we noted in  the game  Rogers-Polgar. White should certainly be quite happy when }6...b6 { appears on the board and while it's long since fallen out of favour amongst grandmasters, at sub-2300 level the move is still quite common, which may suggest that the Barry Attack still carries a certain surprise value in 2023. } )
7. Ne5{ Our favourite leap (bar when  Black plays 6... c5 ! ), and now everything is set for the  h -pawn to hurtle down the board. }
7. c6( { This and the other alternatives to }7...c5 { are surely too slow, but here we can at least be introduced to an important attacking idea for White. } )
8. h4( { This move should by now be second nature, as might well be meeting }8...h5 { with }9.g4! { , but how best to deal with the other possible advance of the black  h -pawn? } )
8. h6
9. h5{ We found three OTB games which reached this position, none of which saw White make this consistent advance, likely due to a misplaced fear of Black closing lines. }
9. g5
10. Bxg5{ The key point. Either Black has lost a rather large pawn or recapturing is forced. }
10. hxg5
11. h6
11. Bxh6
12. Rxh6
12. Kg7
13. Rh1{ The rook is best advised to retreat all the way against Black's prudent defensive idea. }
13. Rh8
14. Kd2{ A slightly unexpected but strong continuation. White makes sure he has a heavy piece on the  h -file and the king is quite safe here. The queen can now recapture on  h1 , the pressure against  f7  is a bit awkward for Black and, if allowed, White would quite like to begin to attack after  Bd3  and  Qf3 . }
