15. Qg3{ The queen is well placed here even with Black's king attempting to run away. The pawn on  h7  is a monster, Black's development a mess and White has far too much for the piece. Two sample continuations: }( { After }15...e6 16.Qxg5 Ke7 17.g4 { , White already has two fine pawns for the piece and after  O-O-O  may well sweep Black from the board with a kingside pawn tsunami, beginning with  f2 - f4 . } )( { Or }15...g4 { when ripping open the  f -file with }16.f3!? { is very dangerous for Black, but }16.Ne2! { rerouting the knight into the attack is even stronger. }16...e6 17.Nf4 Ke7 18.Bg6! { White prepares to crash through on  f7  and Black would do extremely well to survive, not least with his entire queenside still asleep. Note too that the bishop is taboo: }18...fxg6? 19.Nfxg6+ Kd6 20.Nf7+ Kd7 21.Qd6# { . } )
