2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. b6( { Black aims for a double fianchetto, an approach which is too slow against the Barry, as we noted in  the game  Rogers-Polgar. White should certainly be quite happy when }6...b6 { appears on the board and while it's long since fallen out of favour amongst grandmasters, at sub-2300 level the move is still quite common, which may suggest that the Barry Attack still carries a certain surprise value in 2023. } )
7. Ne5{ Our favourite leap (bar when  Black plays 6... c5 ! ), and now everything is set for the  h -pawn to hurtle down the board. }
7. Bb7( 7...e6?! 8.h4! { is business as usual and here White doesn't even really need to worry about Black retreating his knight from  f6  to  d7 . }8...Nfd7!? 9.Qd2!? { Keeping the tension and preparing to go long seems even better than exchanging on  d7 , as White did in Hebden-Astaneh Lopez, Cork 2005. }9...Nxe5 10.Bxe5 { White would be quite happy to exchange off another defender on  g7 .  We should also welcome }10...Bxe5 11.dxe5 { when  f4 - g4  may follow and need not fear a central reaction. After }{   }10...f6 11.Bg3 { , White is clearly for choice, in part because }11...e5? { would cost Black a pawn on  d5 . Two good plans here for White are the cramping  h4 - h5 - h6  and that of combining  O-O-O  with opening lines with  e3 - e4  to exploit White's extra space. } )
8. h4( { We hoped you remembered this advance from  the game  Rogers-Polgar. White wastes no time in getting the kingside offensive under way. We examined }8...c5 { via  a 7... c5  8.h4  Bb7  move order  and in practice Black has more often preferred to first rush a knight to  d7 . Note too that it's no easy matter for Black to keep the kingside closed as }8...h5? { would run straight into }9.g4 { . } )
8. h6{ A surprisingly common mistake. We hope you now remembered from our coverage of  the  7... c6  8.h4 h6  order  what the drill should be for White. }
9. h5{ That's the one! White insists on opening lines even at the cost of a piece. }
9. g5
10. Bxg5
10. hxg5
11. h6{ Already Stockfish has White at almost '+2' and no wonder seeing that Black must either return the piece or make a rather miserable, tail-between-legs retreat into the corner. }
11. Bxh6
12. Rxh6
12. Kg7
13. Rh3( { Placing the rook on a safe square. Here }13.Rh1 Rh8 14.Kd2? { no longer seems at all clear after }14...Nc6 { . } )
13. Rh8
14. Qd2( { White has scored quite well in a few games with Stefanova's }14.Rg3 Rh1+ 15.Bf1 { , but the text seems simpler and at least as strong. White simply wants to go  O-O-O  and doesn't mind an exchange on  h3 : } )
14. Rxh3
15. gxh3
15. Qh8
16. e4{ White threatens  Qxg5 +, as well as  O-O-O  and  Rdg1 , and simply enjoys a significant initiative. }
