7. Bb7( 7...e6?! 8.h4! { is business as usual and here White doesn't even really need to worry about Black retreating his knight from  f6  to  d7 . }8...Nfd7!? 9.Qd2!? { Keeping the tension and preparing to go long seems even better than exchanging on  d7 , as White did in Hebden-Astaneh Lopez, Cork 2005. }9...Nxe5 10.Bxe5 { White would be quite happy to exchange off another defender on  g7 .  We should also welcome }10...Bxe5 11.dxe5 { when  f4 - g4  may follow and need not fear a central reaction. After }{   }10...f6 11.Bg3 { , White is clearly for choice, in part because }11...e5? { would cost Black a pawn on  d5 . Two good plans here for White are the cramping  h4 - h5 - h6  and that of combining  O-O-O  with opening lines with  e3 - e4  to exploit White's extra space. } )
8. h4( { We hoped you remembered this advance from  the game  Rogers-Polgar. White wastes no time in getting the kingside offensive under way. We examined }8...c5 { via  a 7... c5  8.h4  Bb7  move order  and in practice Black has more often preferred to first rush a knight to  d7 . Note too that it's no easy matter for Black to keep the kingside closed as }8...h5? { would run straight into }9.g4 { . } )
8. Nbd7
9. h5{ Getting on with it and, if allowed, White will now strengthen the attack with  hxg6  followed by  Bd3  and  Qf3 . The best defensive try now is for Black to exchange knights on  e5 . }
9. Nxe5
10. Bxe5{ Our standard recapture and now if Black plays slowly White may simply go  Qd2  and 0-0-0, or perhaps first expand with menace through  f2 - f4  and  g2 - g4 . }
10. Ne4( { Worse is }10...Nd7? 11.Bxg7 Kxg7 12.Qd2 { . Black has done well not to lose all eight OTB games we could find which reached this position, since this is clearly too slow. White did, though, go on to record a crushing victory in Pribyl-T.Paehtz, Budapest 1986, and no wonder when you consider that  hxg6  followed by  e3 - e4  is already a sizeable threat. } )
11. Bxg7( { Straightforward play, although those who like tension and don't mind doubled pawns may wish to look into }11.Bd3!? { . } )
11. Kxg7
12. Nxe4{ This exchange leaves Black with a dead-point on  e4  as White settles for a small but rather pleasant edge. }
12. dxe4
13. h6+( { White has scored quite well with }13.Bc4 { , but thanks to AlphaZero we now know all about the dangers of advanced rook's pawns wedged close to the enemy king. } )
13. Kg8
14. Qd2{ White has the greater pawn options and, with them, an edge. Note too, Black's long-term vulnerability on  g7  and the back rank. White will likely go  O-O-O  and  Qc3 , but first is likely to expand with  c2 - c4  and may also find both  d4 - d5  and  f2 - f4  useful advances. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1B) Barry Main Line - 6...Bg4"]
[Black "6...Bg4 with 8...Nbd7 & 10...a6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. Nbd7( { It's a little strange that this move hasn't been somewhat less common than  8...c6 , especially as it also helps to defuse }9.Qb5 { which would now be met by }9...Nb6 { . } )
9. O-O-O{ Housing the king without delay to complete development as White signals that he is quite happy with a double-edged battle. We aim to hurl the  g - and  h -pawns down the board before Black can get too far on the queenside. }( { Now }9...c6 { may look a little slow, but then }10.h4 { reaches a fairly common position, one we'll consider  here  via the   }8...c6 9.h4 Nbd7 10.O-O-O { move order. } )
9. c5
10. h4{ This pawn first as White is actually now threatening  11.h5 . }
10. a6
11. h5{ A powerful sacrifice against Black's slightly slow play and a second one is all set to follow if needed. }
11. Nxh5
12. Rxh5
12. gxh5
13. Qxh5{ White threatens to exchange on  d7  then crash through down the  h -file with  Rh1  and already the engines rather like his chances. }
13. Nf6
14. Qh4
14. cxd4
15. exd4{ Black would do very well to survive this attack and White has two key attacking concepts:  Rd3 - g3  and a slower but equally dangerous set-up in  Rh1  and  g2 - g4 . That latter policy can even be teamed up with  Ne2  (inviting the final piece to the party!) and  Ng3  if needed. }
