13. exd4{ The defence of the knight on  c3  is secure and  h4 - h5  back on the agenda. Black should, however, allow it when White is likely only slightly for choice, rather than prevent it. }
13. h5
14. Bg5( { This created a rather powerful pin in Brousek-Sadowski, correspondence 2005. White simply threatens to exchange on  d7 , then on  f6  and then take on  h5 , badly denigrating the black king's defences, which will quickly also appear rather shaky after }14...hxg4 15.Nxg4 { , strengthening the pin and preparing to break through with  h4 - h5 . } )
