6. Be2
6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. Nbd7( { It's a little strange that this move hasn't been somewhat less common than  8...c6 , especially as it also helps to defuse }9.Qb5 { which would now be met by }9...Nb6 { . } )
9. O-O-O{ Housing the king without delay to complete development as White signals that he is quite happy with a double-edged battle. We aim to hurl the  g - and  h -pawns down the board before Black can get too far on the queenside. }( { Now }9...c6 { may look a little slow, but then }10.h4 { reaches a fairly common position, one we'll consider  here  via the   }8...c6 9.h4 Nbd7 10.O-O-O { move order. } )
9. c5
10. h4{ This pawn first as White is actually now threatening  11.h5 . }
10. Rc8{ A logical try, retaining the central tension while also furthering Black's queenside play. }
11. Rh3( { This is yet to be tried, but makes sense, taking the idea of }11...cxd4 12.exd4 Rxc3 { off the table (White would now simply go }13.Rxc3 { ) }{ , ahead of pushing the  g -pawn. White may also find  Kb1  a fairly useful move to insert, and the position might even quickly become quite sharp. } )
11. h5
12. g4{ Forcing the pace as White spies that it's possible to exchange  g4  for  d5 . Now  13.Bg5  is the main idea, once again angling to leave Black, after exchanges, with a rather weak pawn on  h5 . Will Black, already under early pressure, be able to defend accurately? }
12. cxd4
