[White "1B) Barry Main Line - 6...Bg4"]
[Black "6...Bg4 with 8...c5 9.h4 cxd4 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. c5( { An active, logical and Andrew Martin-endorsed try, if one which is yet to really take off in practice. Mark Hebden has tried to counter it with }9.Qb5 { , but practice has shown }9...cxd4 10.exd4 Qb6 { to be OK for Black, as is definitely }9.dxc5?! Nfd7! { . } )
9. h4{ We refuse to back down and simply want to proceed full-speed ahead with  g2 - g4 ,  O-O-O  and  h4 - h5 . }
9. cxd4
10. exd4
10. Nc6
11. O-O-O{ Whisking the king to safety while overprotecting  d4 . White now very much has ideas of breaking up Black's structure with an exchange on  c6  followed by crashing through with  h4 - h5 . }
11. Rc8{ Black avoids the possibility of  Nxc6   bxc6  and so keeps his rook active. }
12. f3( { White calmly keeps the black knight out of  e4 . Alternatively, }12.h5?! Nxh5 13.Rxh5!? gxh5 14.Qxh5 Qd6 { doesn't seem especially convincing here and   }12.Rh3 Qb6! 13.Nxc6 Rxc6 14.Qxe7 Re8 { has been shown to offer Black decent enough counterplay. } )( { White can consider }12.g4!? { , though. With the centre secure after }12.f3 { , White would be quite happy to see }12...Nxe5?! 13.dxe5 { and is likely to meet anything slow with }13.g4 { or perhaps first }13.Kb1 { . } )
12. Qb6
13. Qe1( { A sneaky little move to overprotect  c3 , while setting a small trap in }13...Nxd4? 14.Be3 { . } )
13. Nb4
14. Kb1( { Now, }14...Rxc3 { can be met by }15.Qxc3 { and all is set for  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5  after all. Both your authors and the engines can only see one way for Black to try and disrupt proceedings. } )
14. Nh5
15. Be3{ Retaining an important bishop. Only now does White threaten  Nd7 , as well as  a2 - a3  followed by  Nxd5 . }
15. Rfd8
16. f4( { Overprotecting  e5  to sidestep Black's idea of }16.a3 Bxe5! 17.dxe5 d4 { . } )( { You may also wonder, why not 16 }g4? { Well, then we would get to see Black's sneaky idea: }16...Ng3! { , and if }17.Rh2 Nf1! { , all designed to drag the white queen away from covering the knight on  c3 . } )( { We very much doubt an opponent would find such resources over the board as Black, so will stop after }16.f4 { when White is threatening  a2 - a3  followed by  g2 - g4  and Black's king's knight would now be trapped after }16...Ng3!? 17.a3! Nxh1 18.axb4 { . } )
