13. Nh5
14. Bh2{ Staying on the  h2 - b8  diagonal to overprotect  e5  and keep Black out of  g3 . }
14. Nxe5
15. Bxe5( { Our standard recapture when there isn't a knight on  f6  and one which reaches an easier position to handle than }15.dxe5 f5! { did in Wittal-Jurjevic, correspondence 2014. } )
15. Bxe5
16. Qxe5{ Perhaps Black is objectively speaking OK here, but White's position looks the more pleasant to us. The  g2 - g4  break is imminent, the knight can be improved via  e2  (it will be effective on the kingside or the  d4 -square should the queens be swapped off on  e5 ), and with so many pieces off the board, the exchange sacrifice is no longer a scary one: }
16. Rxc3
17. bxc3
17. Qa5
18. g4( { Now }18...Qxc3? 19.Rd3 Qb4+ 20.Rb3 { would just cost Black a piece. } )
18. Ng7
19. h5{ White too can very much attack and is simply doing very well, with  Rd3  next up whether or not Black now grabs on  c3 . }
