6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. c6{ Not only cutting out  Qb5  ideas but also offering the black queen a route into the game. }
9. h4{ Our favourite advance and with Black solid but slightly slow on counterplay, it may not come as a surprise that White has scored pretty well from this position in practice. }
9. Qa5
10. O-O-O{ White isn't really castling into 'an attack' here, since Black is unable to conjure up much at all on the queenside. Meanwhile  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5  loom with menace. }
10. Nbd7
11. h5{ White doesn't even need to insert  g2 - g4  here as the knight on  f6  is rather overloaded. }
11. Nxe5
12. dxe5{ The right recapture here, arriving with tempo in a position where White is trying to quickly knock Black out. }
12. Ne4
13. hxg6{ Already White is breaking through to the king, so need not fear Black taking on  c3 . }
13. Nxc3
14. Qh5{ Threatening mate. There are two defensive possibilities, but neither will come close to saving Black: }
14. Nxa2+
15. Kb1
15. fxg6
16. Qxh7+
16. Kf7
17. Bh6( { Simple chess, although }17.e6+!? { is also quite effective here. } )
17. Rg8
18. Rh4( { Or }18.Rd4! { . In any case the threat of  Bxg7  and  Rf4 + is a killer (White's king can always run out to  d2  if needed after ... Nb4  and ... Qa2 +). } )
18. g5
19. Bxg7( { Now }19...Rxg7? 20.Qf5+ { would force mate with checks and there just isn't a defence: }19...Ke6 20.Rh6+ Kd7 21.Bf6 Rge8 22.Bxe7! Rxe7 23.Rd6+ { spells the end with Black losing a rook. } )( { For the record, Blatny-Fette, Vienna 1991, concluded: }19...gxh4 20.Bf6+ Ke6 21.Qxe7+ Kf5 22.Qh7+ Ke6 23.e4! { 1-0 Mate follows, whether with  Rd6 # or after  Qf5 +. } )
