11. Nfd7
12. h5{ The knight on  a4  may look a little out on a limb, but White still has a potentially very dangerous attack and Black would do well to force some exchanges to free his position: }
12. Nxe5
13. Bxe5{ To eliminate the dark-squared defender of the black king. }
13. Bxe5
14. dxe5{ Black isn't about to get mated, but equally the position still looks pleasantly better for White (Vladimir Okhotnik agrees with our analysis, also reaching this position in his coverage in 'The Modernized Barry Attack' where he appends a '+=' symbol), who can always go  b2 - b3  if needed to support his knight. White has ideas of both  e5 - e6  and expansion with  f3 - f4 , and the king should be safe enough on the queenside. }
