2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. c6{ Not only cutting out  Qb5  ideas but also offering the black queen a route into the game. }
9. h4{ Our favourite advance and with Black solid but slightly slow on counterplay, it may not come as a surprise that White has scored pretty well from this position in practice. }
9. Nbd7{ Invariably played after all, if by no means forced. }
10. O-O-O{ Making the king safe before going  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5 , and unsurprisingly White has scored rather well from this position. }
10. Ne4
11. Nxe4{ Naturally White has no desire to see his queenside structure destroyed. }
11. dxe4
12. Kb1( { Once again, this is a useful prophylactic device. In practice White has been unable to resist }12.h5!? { , but after }12...Nxe5 13.dxe5 Qa5 { (attacking  a2  and  e5 ) matters aren't totally clear. As such, White overprotects  a2  and is now ready to finally go  h4 - h5 . } )
12. Nxe5
13. dxe5( { A critical recapture. Now }13...Qa5 { can be met by }14.Qd2! { when White will either follow up with  Qd4  or dominate the open  d -file in the event of an exchange of queens and rook ending. As such, Black may prefer the other way to attack  e5 : } )
13. Qc7( { Now if }14.e6 { Black has }14...Qb6 { , but White can prefer to sacrifice. } )
14. h5
14. Bxe5
15. hxg6{ Opening lines and in a way which might induce a blunder. }
15. fxg6
16. Qc4+( { This is quite the powerful check and already pretty much decisive. It's not so hard to visualise }16...Kg7 17.Bh6+ { or }16...Rf7 17.Rxh7! { , but what about if the king runs into the corner? } )
16. Kh8
17. Rd7( { A powerful and deadly blow, overloading the black queen in view of }17...Qb8? 18.Rxe7 { . } )( { Even after }17...Bxf4 18.Rxc7 Bxc7 19.Qxe4 { , Black should be lost with the extra queen so rampant, but the rook cannot be touched: } )
17. Qxd7
18. Bxe5+
18. Rf6
19. Qf7{ It's quickly going to be mate. }
