8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. c6{ Not only cutting out  Qb5  ideas but also offering the black queen a route into the game. }
9. h4{ Our favourite advance and with Black solid but slightly slow on counterplay, it may not come as a surprise that White has scored pretty well from this position in practice. }
9. Nbd7{ Invariably played after all, if by no means forced. }
10. O-O-O{ Making the king safe before going  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5 , and unsurprisingly White has scored rather well from this position. }
10. Nxe5
11. Bxe5( { This recapture doesn't attack the knight, but it's more important not to allow Black counterplay with }11.dxe5 Nd7 { . }{ White has control and is now all set to strike with  12.h5 . We managed to find 11 over-the-board games which reached this position where one player was rated over 2300 - Black escaped with just three draws, testament to his lack of counterplay and White's pleasant attacking set-up. } )
11. Qa5
12. Kb1( { Prophylaxis against }12...b5 { which can now be met by }13.Qe1! { , and if }13...b4 14.Ne2 { . } )
12. Ne4
13. Nxe4{ Avoiding any catastrophe on the queenside as White shows he is fairly happy to exchange two pairs of pieces, after which he will still enjoy much the safer king position. }
13. dxe4
14. Bxg7
14. Kxg7
15. h5{ While only the major pieces remained and Black was still fairly solid, he was beginning to come under uncomfortable pressure in Izeta Txabarri-Villavicencio Martinez, Las Palmas 1993. White has the better structure and one strong plan is  Rh4 , attacking the dead-point on  e4  while preparing to double on the  h -file. }
