1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. Bg4( { A natural enough move. Black hopes for a solid set-up after }7.h3 Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c6 { . There White can grind away, but here he can do much better than acquire the bishop-pair by making our favourite early knight leap. } )
7. Ne5{ The bishop on  e2  isn't White's most active piece, and while Black is offloading a bishop we often saw struggling for activity in  Chapter 1A,  White should still be fairly happy to see the resulting exchange. }
7. Bxe2
8. Qxe2{ There are no prizes for guessing that an  h2 - h4 - h5  advance is now high on White's radar. There's another possibility here, too, thanks to the queen already being on  e2 : some  Qb5 , generating potentially awkward pressure against  b7  and  d5 . That helps to explain why in practice Black normally prevents the queen raid at this point. }
8. c6{ Not only cutting out  Qb5  ideas but also offering the Black queen a route into the game. }
9. h4{ Our favourite advance and with Black solid but slightly slow on counterplay, it may not come as a surprise that White has scored pretty well from this position in practice. }
9. Nbd7{ Invariably played after all, if by no means forced. }
10. O-O-O{ Making the king safe before going  g2 - g4  and  h4 - h5 , and unsurprisingly White has scored rather well from this position. }
10. Nxe5
11. Bxe5( { This recapture doesn't attack the knight, but it's more important not to allow Black counterplay with }11.dxe5 Nd7 { . }{ White has control and is now all set to strike with  12.h5 . We managed to find 11 over-the-board games which reached this position where one player was rated over 2300 - Black escaped with just three draws, testament to his lack of counterplay and White's pleasant attacking set-up. } )
11. Ne4{ Trying to liquidate so is perhaps the best defensive try. }
12. Nxe4{ White ensures that it's only Black who will be left with doubled pawns after the exchange. }
12. dxe4
13. Bxg7( { This isn't compulsory and }13.h5!? { is possible, but exchanging off the black king's primary defender is rarely a bad policy. } )
13. Kxg7
14. h5{ This not only introduces ideas of a timely  hxg6  and  h6 + (especially useful if Black goes in for a prophylactic ... Rh8  when this rook might become wedged in the corner for some time), but also frees the  h4 -square for a rook. Not only can White target  e4  and the black kingside, but may find both  Kb1  and  c2 - c4  fairly useful moves, tucking the king away and seizing space, respectively. }
14. f5
15. f4{ A powerful advance. If Black doesn't now capture en passant, he will find the pressure on the kingside growing even stronger as White goes  g2 - g4  and  Rdg1 , possibly with  Qh2  flicked in too. }
15. exf3
16. gxf3{ The doubled  e -pawns are gone, as are all the minor pieces, and yet White was clearly better in Dunnington-Berend, Cannes 1992. Not only has he a much safer king and potential pressure down the  g - and  h -files, but there's also the distinct possibility of a central pawn roller beginning with  e3 - e4 . }
