4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c6( { Black's second most popular choice after }6...c5 { , played roughly half as often. } )( { Black shores up  d5 , hints at queenside counterplay and has the notable idea of }7.Ne5 Nfd7! { in mind. } )
7. h4( { This may seem very aggressive, but is fully justified here. White waits for Black to go }7...Nbd7 { before leaping forward with }8.Ne5 { . } )( { We would prefer to avoid falling in with Black's plans with }7.Ne5 Nfd7 { , although Vladimir Okhotnik has recently suggested that White may then be able to still fight for an advantage in the rather unusual position that arises after }8.h4 f6 9.Nf3 { . That's in a book published while we were writing this course, 'The Modernized Barry Attack' by Okhotnik himself, which provides fairly comprehensive coverage of the opening and contains some very interesting ideas. } )( { We have full confidence in }7.h4 { , which is actually far from risky as you'll quickly see, but if the advance really feels too much for you, then you may prefer the prophylactic }7.h3 { , transposing to a position we'll consider in  Chapter 3A  via the   }4...c6 5.h3 Bg7 6.e3 O-O 7.Be2 { move order. } )( { After }7.h4!? { Black's most common response by some margin in practice has been }7...Bg4 { when }8.Ne5 Bxe2 9.Qxe2 { takes us right back into the realm of  Chapter 1B.  } )
7. Qb6{ Counterattacking against  b2 . }
8. Na4( { White's most direct response. Black is fine after }8.Rb1 Bg4 { as White can no longer castle queenside. } )( { Richard used to play }8.a3!? { here, when }8...Qxb2?? 9.Na4 { traps the queen and   }8...Bg4 9.Qd2!? { is possible, but after   }8...Bf5 { White probably has to switch to a positional approach after all as it's hard to fully believe in }9.Qd2!? Qxb2 10.Rb1 Qxa3 11.O-O { , a double pawn sacrifice. Do feel free to check it out, though. } )( { Instead, with }8.Na4 { White begins to annex space on the queenside and may well follow up by obtaining a clamp on the  c5 -square with  c2 - c3  and  b2 - b4 . } )
8. Qa5+
9. c3{ The only really logical way to meet the check and now  b2 - b4  is imminent. }
9. Ne4
10. h5( { We prefer this to the overly creative }10.Ng5 { of Vallin-Nataf, French Team Championship 2004. There's no reason for White not to combine play on both sides of the board and now the ideal plan would be  hxg6  followed by  b2 - b4 ,  Ne5  and  f2 - f3  to evict the intruder from  e4 . } )
10. b5
11. Nc5{ The only real choice. }
11. Nxc5
12. dxc5{ White would now quite like to take control with  hxg6  followed by  Qd2  then  Ne5  or even  e3 - e4 , looking to attack on the kingside after all. As such, Black should probably react: }
12. b4
13. a3{ A powerful pawn sacrifice. }
13. bxc3
14. b4{ An essential advance to hold everything together before continuing to go forwards. }
14. Qd8
15. hxg6
15. hxg6
16. Be5{ White contests the long diagonal and must be for choice here with his extra space and kingside possibilities, while the  c3 -pawn is surely not long for this world with moves such as  Qd4  in the offering. }
