1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c6( { Black's second most popular choice after }6...c5 { , played roughly half as often. } )( { Black shores up  d5 , hints at queenside counterplay and has the notable idea of }7.Ne5 Nfd7! { in mind. } )
7. h4( { This may seem very aggressive, but is fully justified here. White waits for Black to go }7...Nbd7 { before leaping forward with }8.Ne5 { . } )( { We would prefer to avoid falling in with Black's plans with }7.Ne5 Nfd7 { , although Vladimir Okhotnik has recently suggested that White may then be able to still fight for an advantage in the rather unusual position that arises after }8.h4 f6 9.Nf3 { . That's in a book published while we were writing this course, 'The Modernized Barry Attack' by Okhotnik himself, which provides fairly comprehensive coverage of the opening and contains some very interesting ideas. } )( { We have full confidence in }7.h4 { , which is actually far from risky as you'll quickly see, but if the advance really feels too much for you, then you may prefer the prophylactic }7.h3 { , transposing to a position we'll consider in  Chapter 3A  via the   }4...c6 5.h3 Bg7 6.e3 O-O 7.Be2 { move order. } )( { After }7.h4!? { Black's most common response by some margin in practice has been }7...Bg4 { when }8.Ne5 Bxe2 9.Qxe2 { takes us right back into the realm of  Chapter 1B.  } )
7. Qa5{ Pinning the knight on  c3  and so threatening ... Ne4  is certainly logical. }
8. a3( { White has usually gone }8.Qd2 { here, but then }8...Bg4 { gives Black an improved version of  Line 1B,   since }9.Ne5 Bxe2 10.Qxe2 { would leave him with the useful extra move ... Qa5  over the main line there. } )( { Instead, with }8.a3 { White prepares to hit back with a timely  b2 - b4 . Black has two fairly critical responses: } )
8. Bg4
9. Ne5( { Forcing the pace and following our usual approach in such positions. Here there's also }9.Qd2 { if you want to keep pieces on and which certainly cuts out ... Ne4  possibilities. } )
9. Bxe2
10. Qxe2{ Now White is all set to castle long and proceed as normal on the kingside, so Black is likely to try and exploit the pin. }
10. Ne4
11. b4( { The simplest approach and engine-approved, although, depending on style and taste, you may wish to prefer }11.h5!? { , and if }11...Nxc3 12.Qd2 { , pinning to regain the piece. } )
11. Nxc3
12. bxa5
12. Nxe2
13. Kxe2( { Connecting the rooks and the king should, of course, be well placed here for any endgame. White has possibilities on both flanks, decent dark-square control and the better knight. It may not add up to a large advantage after careful defence, something which }13...Na6? 14.Rab1 { would not be, leading to White winning a clear pawn. } )
13. b6
14. Nd3( { Keeping pieces on, as White hopes to dominate the black knight after }14...bxa5? 15.Nc5 { . He will now play to obtain some pressure down the  b -file and likely also for the  c2 - c4  break. } )
