[Black "6...c6 7.h4 Nbd7 8.Ne5 h5 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c6( { Black's second most popular choice after }6...c5 { , played roughly half as often. } )( { Black shores up  d5 , hints at queenside counterplay and has the notable idea of }7.Ne5 Nfd7! { in mind. } )
7. h4( { This may seem very aggressive, but is fully justified here. White waits for Black to go }7...Nbd7 { before leaping forward with }8.Ne5 { . } )( { We would prefer to avoid falling in with Black's plans with }7.Ne5 Nfd7 { , although Vladimir Okhotnik has recently suggested that White may then be able to still fight for an advantage in the rather unusual position that arises after }8.h4 f6 9.Nf3 { . That's in a book published while we were writing this course, 'The Modernized Barry Attack' by Okhotnik himself, which provides fairly comprehensive coverage of the opening and contains some very interesting ideas. } )( { We have full confidence in }7.h4 { , which is actually far from risky as you'll quickly see, but if the advance really feels too much for you, then you may prefer the prophylactic }7.h3 { , transposing to a position we'll consider in  Chapter 3A  via the   }4...c6 5.h3 Bg7 6.e3 O-O 7.Be2 { move order. } )( { After }7.h4!? { Black's most common response by some margin in practice has been }7...Bg4 { when }8.Ne5 Bxe2 9.Qxe2 { takes us right back into the realm of  Chapter 1B.  } )
7. Nbd7{ Natural development, so this has been Black's joint second most popular choice, along with advancing the  h -pawn. }
8. Ne5{ Only now that the  d7 -square is in use by the other black knight does White advance. This position can come about from a few different move orders and White has scored fairly well. Notably, while it has featured at all levels of play, this position does seem to be especially common at amateur and sub-2300 level, often with Black seemingly just relying on solid moves to get by against the Barry. That's a slightly risky policy when White's play is quite aggressive and here, with the  h4 - h5  hanging over his head, Black usually opts either for some central knight action or to rule out  h4 - h5  for good by deploying their own  h -pawn, while other moves don't challenge our plan. }
8. h5{ Black tries to rule out  h4 - h5  for good. }
9. Qd2{ A sensible, natural move, facilitating  O-O-O  while keeping  f2 - f3  in reserve. }( { The immediate }9.f3 { has been slightly more popular, but after }9...Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Qb6 { we couldn't find anything amazing for White, which }11.Na4 Qa5+ 12.b4?! Nd7! { certainly isn't. } )
9. Nxe5
10. Bxe5( { The right recapture, not least as the direct tries after }10.dxe5?! Nd7 { don't seem to lead anywhere for White, and now Black has often hurled his  b -pawn into the fray. } )
10. Ne4{ Simplifying so is certainly a safer policy, not least as White is now fairly obliged to exchange on  e4 . }
11. Nxe4
11. Bxe5
12. dxe5{ Allowing further simplification, but also definitely the best move here with Black's pawn on  h5  (were it on  h6  White would have some extra options, as we'll see). }
12. dxe4
13. O-O-O( { If you're really determined to retain the queens, Okhotnik's }13.Qc3!? Be6 14.Rg1!? { is probably the best try when the critical response is }14...Qd5 { . After going long, White has ideas of both  Qc3  and  Qb4 , when the  e4 -pawn might well prove quite sickly, so Black should probably continue to hoover. This position could, of course, also arise via }{   }11...dxe4 12.O-O-O Bxe5 13.dxe5 { and there, White could also consider   }12.Bxg7 Kxg7 13.f3!? { , looking to seize the initiative. } )
13. Qxd2+( 13...Be6?! 14.Qb4 Qc7 15.Qxe4 { not only left White a pawn up in M.Marshall-B. Pedersen, Copenhagen 2005, but also placed the idea of a powerful pawn break with  g2 - g4  right back on the agenda. } )
14. Rxd2
14. Bf5
15. Rhd1{ While Black is undeniably very solid here, White does own the only open file and Black is slightly hampered by both the less active bishop and the dead-point on  e4 . White will likely angle to probe with  Rd4 , possibly then switching the rook to the left, or more likely seizing space with  a2 - a4 , after which  b2 - b3  then  Kb2  will help bring the king into the game. After that White might look to go  R1d2 ,  Bc4  and  e5 - e6 , swapping a pawn to invade on the seventh rank. }
