[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1C) Barry Main Line - 6...c6"]
[Black "6...c6 7.h4 Nbd7 8.Ne5 Nxe5 #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c6( { Black's second most popular choice after }6...c5 { , played roughly half as often. } )( { Black shores up  d5 , hints at queenside counterplay and has the notable idea of }7.Ne5 Nfd7! { in mind. } )
7. h4( { This may seem very aggressive, but is fully justified here. White waits for Black to go }7...Nbd7 { before leaping forward with }8.Ne5 { . } )( { We would prefer to avoid falling in with Black's plans with }7.Ne5 Nfd7 { , although Vladimir Okhotnik has recently suggested that White may then be able to still fight for an advantage in the rather unusual position that arises after }8.h4 f6 9.Nf3 { . That's in a book published while we were writing this course, 'The Modernized Barry Attack' by Okhotnik himself, which provides fairly comprehensive coverage of the opening and contains some very interesting ideas. } )( { We have full confidence in }7.h4 { , which is actually far from risky as you'll quickly see, but if the advance really feels too much for you, then you may prefer the prophylactic }7.h3 { , transposing to a position we'll consider in  Chapter 3A  via the   }4...c6 5.h3 Bg7 6.e3 O-O 7.Be2 { move order. } )( { After }7.h4!? { Black's most common response by some margin in practice has been }7...Bg4 { when }8.Ne5 Bxe2 9.Qxe2 { takes us right back into the realm of  Chapter 1B.  } )
7. Nbd7{ Natural development, so this has been Black's joint second most popular choice, along with advancing the  h -pawn. }
8. Ne5{ Only now that the  d7 -square is in use by the other black knight does White advance. This position can come about from a few different move orders and White has scored fairly well. Notably, while it has featured at all levels of play, this position does seem to be especially common at amateur and sub-2300 level, often with Black seemingly just relying on solid moves to get by against the Barry. That's a slightly risky policy when White's play is quite aggressive and here, with the  h4 - h5  hanging over his head, Black usually opts either for some central knight action or to rule out  h4 - h5  for good by deploying their own  h -pawn, while other moves don't challenge our plan. }
8. Nxe5( { Black's most popular choice, possibly sometimes played by a realisation that }9.dxe5 Nd7 { must be fine for them. } )
9. Bxe5{ The right recapture once again and now Black's most common choice has been to try and simplify further. }
9. b5( { This feels a little slow here, especially as Black doesn't really want to allow White to control the queenside too after a rushed }10.-- b4 11.Na4 { . } )
10. h5
10. a5
11. Bd3( { Improving over the }11.g4 { of Megaranto-Al Zendani, Zaozhuang 2012, to cut out ... Ne4  ideas, prepare a potential regrouping square for the white knight on  c3  and while being prepared to sacrifice a pawn to further White's kingside play. } )( { Finally, note that after }11...a4 { White may now either halt Black for the time being with }12.a3 { or continue on the kingside with }12.hxg6 fxg6 13.f3 { , possibly followed by  Ne2 . } )
11. Nxh5
12. Rxh5{ Throwing more wood on the fire in pursuit of the king on  g8  and this is actually quite a powerful exchange sacrifice. }
12. gxh5
13. Bxh7+{ A further and decisive sacrificial blow. }
13. Kxh7
14. Qxh5+
14. Kg8
15. Bxg7{ It's pretty much all over, not least as Black will be mated if he recaptures on  g7 : }
15. Kxg7
16. Qg5+
16. Kh7
17. O-O-O( { Remarkably it's only mate in 14 according to the engines (after }17...Qd7 18.Rh1 Qh3 { ) }{ . } )
