*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2) Barry Main Line - 6...c5 7.dxc5 Other Moves"]
[Black "6...c5 7.dxc5 Ne4"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c5{ After all the standard moves from White, we now come on to Black's most popular and most critical sixth move, reacting without delay in the centre. }
7. dxc5( { A change of approach, but one we hope will both surprise opponents and, from a theoretical perspective, ask some fairly challenging questions. As we saw in Hebden-Nunn, Black has established a few reasonable lines against }7.Ne5 { , White's traditional Barry choice:  • the }7...cxd4 8.exd4 Nfd7 { of that game;  • the   }7...Nc6 8.O-O Bf5 { set-up. } )( { The }7.dxc5 { line was pioneered in the 1980s and early 1990s by the now Bangladeshi GM Niaz Murshed. Back then Julian Hodgson and even Mark Hebden dabbled in it and more recently, the Indonesian no.1 Susanto Megaranto has rather flown the flag for White. We should mention too that the idea has also caught the eye of Jorden van Foreest and even Fabiano Caruana, who played it against Peter Svidler in the 2021 Saint Louis Rapid.  With }7.dxc5 { , White treats the position as a reversed Catalan where he enjoys active development. Pressure is exerted down the  d -file against  d5  and it doesn't initially look so easy for Black to regain his pawn. Black has two main responses, of roughly equal popularity amongst grandmasters, but the more obvious text move is the somewhat more common choice at lower levels:  2A) }7...Qa5 { will be examined  here.   2B) }7...Nbd7 { will be examined  here.   First we should see what happens if Black prefers just 'to develop'. } )
7. Ne4{ This has been extremely rare, but is not without logic, threatening to take on  c3 , as well as  c5 . }( { In contrast, }7...Nfd7? 8.Nxd5 { would just be excellent for White. } )
8. Nxd5{ The proof of the pudding must lie in the eating, so White boldly devours the en prise pawn, in the process threatening  Nc7 . }
8. Bxb2
9. Bc7( { Forcing the pace. Instead, }9.Nc7 Nc3 { wasn't at all clear in J.Van Foreest-Deepan Chakkravarthy, Basel 2017. } )( { However, there's absolutely nothing wrong with }9.Rb1 { should you prefer to be solid, meeting }9...Qa5+ { with }10.Kf1 { . Alternatively, Black can go for }{   }9...Bc3+ 10.Nxc3 Nxc3 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 12.Rb3 { or }9...Nc3 10.Nf6+! exf6 11.Qxd8 Rxd8 12.Rxb2 { . } )
9. Qd7
10. Be5{ The point of White's play. He will now dominate the centre and the board unless Black accepts the exchange sacrifice. }
10. Bxa1
11. Bxa1
11. Nc6
12. h4( { The position isn't at all clear and }12.O-O { followed by  c2 - c4  also supplies full compensation, but we quite like White's compensation for the exchange: a strong knight on  d5 , kingside initiative and control of the dark squares. Already not only is  h4 - h5  a threat, but also  Ng5  looking to open up the  h -file. Yes, Black can exchange the queens, but that is not a panacea. } )
12. e6
13. Nf6+
13. Nxf6
14. Bxf6{ Now White would go  Qa1  or even  Qd6  if allowed, so Black should exchange. }
14. Qxd1+
15. Kxd1{ The engines slightly prefer White and with good reason. That bishop on  f6  is a monster, seriously inconveniencing the black rooks, while the extra pawn on  c5  is also quite useful. White may still go  h4 - h5 , while  Ng5 - e4  is another good idea, continuing to dominate the dark squares. }
