7. Nc6
8. O-O{ Calmly does it. Now that the king is safe, White may be able to contemplate a timely  Nb5 , with  Nd4  or  Nd2 - b3  also high on the agenda and all the while Black is still a pawn down. }
8. Ne4
9. Nxe4( { Here this seems stronger than allowing }9.Nxd5 Bxb2 { . } )
9. dxe4
10. Nd2( { Now if }10...e5 11.Bg3 { when White isn’t inconvenienced by }11...f5 12.f3! { followed by  Bc4 + or even  Nc4 , so Black should likely take on  b2 . } )( { Going straight for the  e4 -pawn improves over the }10.Qxd8 { of Vescovi-Valenzuela Fuentealba, Guarapuava 1995, when }10...Nxd8! { wouldn't have been so clear, and if }11.Ng5? h6 12.Nxe4 e5 13.Bg3 f5 { . } )
10. Bxb2
11. Nxe4( { A thematic and decent exchange sacrifice. There's also the simple }11.Rb1 { when }11...Bg7 12.Nxe4 Qa5 13.Bc4 { shouldn't give Black quite enough for a pawn. } )
11. Bxa1
12. Qxa1{ White threatens  Bh6  and also has ideas of both  Bf3  and  Rd1 . With such piece activity, there must be at least enough for the exchange. }
12. f6
13. Rd1
13. Qa5
14. Bh6( { White is regaining the exchange and should be slightly for choice, with  Bc4+  likely to follow. Yes, Black must avoid greed in view of }14...Rf7? 15.Bc4 e6 16.Nxf6+ { . } )
14. Re8
15. Bc4+
15. Kh8
16. Nxf6{ Already Black has to resign, since, of course, it's quickly mate if he takes the knight and, in any case, it's mate in 8 according to the computer! }
