7. dxc5
7. Qa5{ The obvious choice as Black plays to regain the pawn, while threatening ... Ne4 . }
8. Nd2( { Wisely keeping Black out of  e4  as }8...Ne4? { can now be well met by }9.Nxd5 { , breaking the pin, threatening  Nb3  and so pretty much forcing Black's next move. } )
8. Qxc5
9. Nb3{ With tempo. As we've already noted, White's knights now appear quite harmonious and he may be able to begin to exert pressure against the  d5 -pawn. }
9. Qc6{ This much less common choice keeps  d5  secure, but also slightly interferes with Black's development. }
10. O-O{ Continuing development. White may now look to exert some pressure with  Bf3  and/or annex some useful space with  a2 - a4 , while also enjoying handy control of  e5  (even  Be5  may be useful). }( { We¡ll examine }10...a6 11.Bf3 { in  the illustrative game  Megaranto-Mohammad Fahad, Asian Nations Online Cup (rapid) 2020. } )
10. e6
11. a4( { Annexing some useful space rather than get embroiled in the complications of }11.Nb5 a6! 12.Nc7 Ra7 { . } )( { After }11.a4! { , though, }11...-- 12.Nb5 { is a threat followed by playing on the dark squares, as with }12...Na6 13.Be5 { or }12...a6 13.N3d4! { . } )
11. a6
12. a5{ White's grip on the queenside supplied a small but pleasant edge in Krishna-Salem, Titled Tuesday Blitz 2022. Already  Na4  is something of a threat and White might also play to open up the centre with  Bf3 ,  Re1  and  e3 - e4 . }
