7. dxc5
7. Qa5{ The obvious choice as Black plays to regain the pawn, while threatening ... Ne4 . }
8. Nd2( { Wisely keeping Black out of  e4  as }8...Ne4? { can now be well met by }9.Nxd5 { , breaking the pin, threatening  Nb3  and so pretty much forcing Black's next move. } )
8. Qxc5
9. Nb3{ With tempo. As we've already noted, White's knights now appear quite harmonious and he may be able to begin to exert pressure against the  d5 -pawn. }
9. Qb6{ Keeping  c6  free for the knight on  b8  and Black would be quite happy to exchange  d5  for  b2 . }
10. a4( { Our main recommendation, seizing space without further delay. White should avoid }10.Nxd5? Nxd5 11.Qxd5 Bxb2 { and }10.Nb5 Ne8 { is fine for Black. } )( { However, of course, Blatny did make a reasonable case for }10.Bf3 { in Blatny-Schmidt, Austrian League 2014, as we've already seen. } )
10. Nc6
11. a5( { Consistent, of course, and it's also quite nice to drive the black queen back to base. }11...Qb4?? 12.Ra4 { would not be wise. } )
11. Qd8
12. O-O{ Making the king safe as White continues to make all the moves which will definitely be useful. There's no rush to get in  a5 - a6 . Notably Murshed has had this position seven times on the database, winning four, drawing two and losing just the first of those games. }
12. h6{ Black wants to break with ... e5  without then being pinned by  Bg5 . }( { Murshed has tried }13.h3 { and even }13.Kh1!? { here and, once again, there's also another prophylactic move. } )
13. Bg3{ Now with  Qd2  and  Rfd1  White will be quick to obtain some pressure down the  d -file if Black plays slowly. }
13. e5
14. Bh4{ Another bishop move, but now  d5  is attacked. White should be fairly happy to provoke a potentially weakening ... g5  (after  Bg3  even  f2 - f4  may then be an idea), and may also look to increase the pressure with a timely  Nc5  (to hit  b7  and harass a bishop on  e6 ). }
