4. Bg7
5. e3
5. O-O
6. Be2
6. c5
7. dxc5
7. Nbd7{ Black aims to regain the pawn without having to move their queen, an ambitious policy if also a theoretically-approved one. }
8. Nxd5{ This is likely to come as a surprise to opponents. White threatens  Nc7  after capturing the gambitted pawn in a fashion that the books used to denote as '?', but then along came a certain important new idea (see  here ). }
8. Nxd5
9. Qxd5{ Going two pawns to the good and White should now be quite happy to see Black regain one of those on  b2 . }
9. Qa5+{ A safer choice, even if it's not an obvious equaliser (unless Black has studied the line in some depth and/or is a fan of that fine two-part course, 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defense', where Gawain Jones endorsed the check. }
10. Qd2( { The best choice and definitely not }10.c3? Bxc3+! { . } )
10. Qxd2+
11. Kxd2( { The most ambitious try, connecting the rooks and keeping the king in the centre for the endgame. Black is OK after }11.Nxd2 Bxb2 12.Rb1 Bc3 { , although if a draw is unusually good for you, here White does have }13.c6! bxc6 14.Rb3 Ba5 15.Ra3 { when Black is best advised to repeat moves with }15...Bb4 { as otherwise,  Bf3  is a bit awkward. } )( { After the king recapture, White would love to go  c2-c3  then  Rhd1  and will meet }11...Nxc5 { with }12.Be5 { , so Black is still best advised to take on  b2 . } )
11. Bxb2
12. Rab1{ With a threat and now Black must be slightly careful over retreating the bishop. }
12. Bf6( { Jones's recommendation. Here he thought that White should be happy to return the extra pawn with }13.c6 { , but we can also try and be a little more ambitious. } )
13. Rb5
13. e5
14. Bg3( { Keeping an eye on  e5  and playing to retain control makes sense, although fans of complexity may wish to consider copying Woodard-Ingersol, correspondence 2013, which saw }14.Bg5!? a6 15.Ra5 e4 16.c6 { and a strategically most unclear scenario arise. } )( { After the calmer }14.Bg3 { , White can now meet }14...e4? { with }15.Nd4 { . } )
14. a6
15. Rb4( { This seems the most challenging response whereas }15.Ra5 { is fairly well met by }15...Bd8 { , taking control of  e4 . } )
15. Rd8
16. Bd3{ Black may be OK here if he defends precisely, but White is risking little, ready to swap  c5  for  e5  and also all set to go  Rhb1  or just  Rc4 . }
