7. Nbd7{ Black aims to regain the pawn without having to move their queen, an ambitious policy if also a theoretically-approved one. }
8. Nxd5{ This is likely to come as a surprise to opponents. White threatens  Nc7  after capturing the gambitted pawn in a fashion that the books used to denote as '?', but then along came a certain important new idea (see move 10). }
8. Nxd5
9. Qxd5{ Going two pawns to the good and White should now be quite happy to see Black regain one of those on  b2 . }
9. Bxb2
10. O-O( { First played in 2010, this is the key idea for White, one which even has Fabiano Caruana's seal of approval. White relies on speedy development and is happy to sacrifice the exchange to take control of the dark squares. Instead, as shown by older theory, }10.Rb1? Qa5+ 11.Kf1 Bg7 { just leaves Black doing pretty well.  After castling, White threatens to dominate the board with  11.Rab1 , so in correspondence and over-the-board play Black has always accepted the offer. } )
10. Bxa1
11. Rxa1
11. Qa5{ Activating the queen forces the pace, has been standard and seems best. }
12. Bh6{ Forcing the pace and now Black should take on  c5  before White captures on  f8  or even goes  Qd4 . }
12. Qc3
13. Rd1{ This gives White a handy extra tempo and even introduces the threat of  Bc4 . }
13. Nf6
14. Qb3( { This improves over }14.Qe5 { from the stem game, Etienne-Johann, German League 2010. }{ White regroups with tempo, prepares to go after  f7  with  Bc4  and  Ng5 , and Black cannot save the exchange: } )
14. Qxb3
15. cxb3
15. Re8
16. Bb5{ The rook is out of safe squares and White a pretty useful pawn up. }
