13. Qb3{ As played by Caruana. White retains the queens, keeps a firm eye on  f7  and is ready to regain the exchange. }
13. Re8( { Or }13...Rd8 14.Ng5 { and suddenly Black is in huge trouble, as }14...Ne5 { can be simply met by }15.f4 { .  After }{   }14...e6 15.Rd1 { , Black is badly tangled up and probably just lost. White already threatens }15...-- 16.Nxe6! { because }16...fxe6 17.Qxe6+ Kh8 18.Rxd7! { forces mate, and ideas of  Ne4  in conjunction with  Qb2  will also be rather potent. } )
14. Ng5( { Now }14...e6?! 15.Bb5 { would leave Black's dark squares beginning to creak quite badly. Another attempt is to defend with the queen. } )
14. Qf5
15. Rd1( { Calmly inviting the final piece to the party. White now threatens }15...-- 16.Rd4 { followed by  Rf4  or }16...e5 17.Rd6 { as our active pieces supply slightly more than enough for the exchange. If the knight leaves  d7  there's always at least  Bb5  to regain the exchange and  e3 - e4 - e5  might prove a useful space-gaining advance. } )
