[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. c6
5. h3{ Hebden's preference and simply a good move, prophylactically ruling out ... Bg4  and also giving the Barry bishop a retreat square in the event of any early ... Nh5 . White is now ready to continue kingside development with  e2 - e3  and  Be2 . }
5. Qb6
6. Rb1( { A simpler choice than }6.Na4!? Qa5+ 7.c3 { . White protects  b2  and is now ready to go  e2 - e3  and  Be2  after all. Perhaps Black might argue that White won't be castling long, but that is very rarely the aim after  5.h3 . } )
6. Bg7
7. e3
7. Nbd7
8. Be2{ The first phase of simple development is complete, and next, White will castle. }
8. O-O
9. O-O
9. Re8
10. Bh2{ Perhaps a slightly surprising choice, but this prophylactic retreat has been used by both Hebden and Aronian. By ensuring that ... Nh5  won't attack the bishop, White pretty much takes ... e5  off the table, leaving Black struggling for counterplay and with the queen on  b6  looking slightly misplaced. White can now exploit the early  Rb1  to seize some useful space with  b2 - b4  and may also look to exploit his superior development with  Bd3  and  e3 - e4 . }
10. e6
11. b4{ Consistently seizing space and clamping down on the  c5 -square. White is now all set to annex further space with  Bd3 ,  Re1  and  e3 - e4 , all as Black begins to look a little cramped. }
11. Qd8
12. Bd3
12. a5
13. a3( { White enjoyed a small but pleasant edge in Hebden-Rayner, Hastings 1999. Black can open the  a -file, but that may not benefit him: for example, after }13...axb4 14.axb4 Ra3 15.Qd2 { White will be ready to go  Ra1 .  Meanwhile, White is all set to start opening up the centre with  Re1  and  e3 - e4 , which should favour his more actively placed minor pieces. } )
