[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. c6
5. h3{ Hebden's preference and simply a good move, prophylactically ruling out ... Bg4  and also giving the Barry bishop a retreat square in the event of any early ... Nh5 . White is now ready to continue kingside development with  e2 - e3  and  Be2 . }
5. Bg7{ Invariably played as Black gets back to completing the fianchetto begun on move two. }
6. e3( { Having ruled out  ...Bg4  and ensured that }6...Nh5?! { doesn't help Black, White gets back to kingside development. } )
6. O-O( { This isn't forced, but after Black's main alternative, }6...Nbd7 { , play is extremely likely to transpose following }7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O { . } )
7. Be2( { A simple choice and this position can also arise via   }4...Bg7 5.e3 O-O 6.Be2 c6 7.h3 { ( }7.h4!? { was our main recommendation here in  Chapter 1C ). } )( { With this  4...c6  move order, here White can also consider a slightly more active approach in }7.Bd3!? { , as Hebden has also played. After }7.Be2 { , Black has very occasionally been known to go }7...c5!? { after all, when White should simply play }8.dxc5 { , as per  Chapter Two lines  where the inclusion of  h2 - h3  is never going to be a bad thing. } )
7. Nbd7{ Black's main choice by some margin, ensuring they can meet any  Ne5  with an exchange of knights. }
8. O-O( { Simple chess, making the king safe before looking to seize any space. Those who desire a more unbalanced position may also wish to look into Blatny's }8.g4!? { , provocatively seizing space and as successfully played by another leading Barry expert in Hebden-Palliser, Scarborough 1996. } )
8. Re8{ This has actually been Black's most popular choice in practice, optimistically hoping to get in ... e5  one day. }
9. Bh2{ While Black wasn't yet really threatening ... Nh5 ;  Bh2   e5  (White would get in  Bxh5  after exchanges on  e5 ), this is still a good prophylactic retreat, taking ... e5  ideas largely off the table and challenging Black to show that his rook isn't simply misplaced on  e8 . }( { If Black inserts }9...a6 10.a4 { (Naturally, White plays for a queenside clamp with  a4-a5 .) }10...Nh5?! { , White reacts in the centre before Black can get in ... e5  and after }11.e4!? dxe4 12.Nxe4 { , now }12...e5? 13.dxe5 { would just win material for White thanks to the presence of the queens on the  d -file. Note too again just how powerful the bishop on  h2  is. } )( { Alternatively, Black can try   }12...Nhf6 { but }13.Ned2! { kept pieces on to leave Black cramped and clearly worse in Bluebaum-Zhukov, Internet }{ (blitz) }{ 2021. White may clamp down further with  Nc4  and  a4 - a5 , while both  c2 - c3  and  Re1  are also likely to prove useful. } )
9. Ne4
10. Nxe4{ Ever a good response to an early ... Ne4 ; White avoids any damage on  c3  and prepares to leave Black with a dead point on  e4 . }
10. dxe4
11. Nd2{ A simpler and safer choice than going to  g5 . Now White may increase the pressure against  e4  with  c2 - c3  and  Qc2 , and can very much also seize space on the queenside, not least with  a2 - a4 . }
11. f5( { Here, White went for an active approach with }12.Bc4+ Kh8 13.f3 { in Srienz-Moravcik, Bratislava 1991, but there's no need for this change of structure. } )
12. c3{ White prepares to annoy Black slightly with  Qb3 + and would like to obtain a firm grip on the position with that in conjunction with  a2 - a4  and  Nc4 . Black can hit back in the centre, but not come anywhere close to equalising. }
12. e5
13. Qb3+
13. Kh8
14. Nc4{ White threatens  Nd6  and may also just follow up with  a2 - a4  and  Rfd1 , leaving Black struggling to untangle and the Barry bishop on  h2  something of a potential monster. }
