6. O-O( { This isn't forced, but after Black's main alternative, }6...Nbd7 { , play is extremely likely to transpose following }7.Be2 O-O 8.O-O { . } )
7. Be2( { A simple choice and this position can also arise via   }4...Bg7 5.e3 O-O 6.Be2 c6 7.h3 { ( }7.h4!? { was our main recommendation here in  Chapter 1C ). } )( { With this  4...c6  move order, here White can also consider a slightly more active approach in }7.Bd3!? { , as Hebden has also played. After }7.Be2 { , Black has very occasionally been known to go }7...c5!? { after all, when White should simply play }8.dxc5 { , as per  Chapter Two lines  where the inclusion of  h2 - h3  is never going to be a bad thing. } )
7. Nbd7{ Black's main choice by some margin, ensuring they can meet any  Ne5  with an exchange of knights. }
8. O-O( { Simple chess, making the king safe before looking to seize any space. Those who desire a more unbalanced position may also wish to look into Blatny's }8.g4!? { , provocatively seizing space and as successfully played by another leading Barry expert in Hebden-Palliser, Scarborough 1996. } )
