4. Bf4( { Having examined the main lines of the Barry, and before we turn our attention to the modern trend for }4...Bg7 5.Nb5 { , there are a few sidelines for Black we should consider. } )
4. a6( { While lagging a long way behind }4...Bg7 { and }4...c6 { in the popularity stakes, this has actually been Black's third most common move. } )( { Now, a simple approach for White is }5.Qd2!? { , intending  Bh6  and/or  Ne5 , and it's also possible to stick to our usual approach: } )
5. e3( { Now Black almost always goes }5...Bg7 { when we'll see }6.Be2 { below via a   }4...Bg7 5.e3 a6 6.Be2 { move order. See  here.  }{ There's certainly no need to fear Black trying to make aggressive use of  4...a6 , which is seemingly usually played solely to rule out  Nb5 . } )
5. b5
6. Ne5{ Thematically leaping forwards and now  h2 - h4  is likely to follow, either before or after  Be2 . }( { White would also be quite happy to see }6...b4?! 7.Na4 { , which merely drives the knight towards a fine post on  c5 . } )
6. Bb7
7. h4( { Aggressive play, but justified aggression, as we shall see. Now }7...h5 8.Bd3!? { would leave Black potentially vulnerable on  g6  and White might also then prod the queenside with  a2 - a4 , intending to regroup with ... b4 ;  Ne2 . } )
7. Bg7
8. h5{ This dangerous advance already left White with a pretty handy early initiative in Sharbaf-Darban Vaighani, Kish 2005, with ideas of  Qf3  and  g2 - g4 , as well as just  Bd3  and  hxg6  or even  h5 - h6 . The pawn is en prise, but it would take a brave or foolhardy opponent to capture it: }
8. Nxh5
9. Rxh5
9. gxh5
10. Qxh5( { A powerful exchange sacrifice. Black would now be blown away after }10...O-O? 11.Bd3 { . } )( 10...Bxe5 11.Bxe5 { also spells rather bad news for Black, and even defending  f7  is far from a panacea: } )
10. Rf8
11. Nd3( { This sneaky retreat is even stronger than taking on  h7 . White prepares to invade on  c5 , will meet }11...Nd7 { with }12.Nxd5 { , has ideas of  Qh2  with a rather awkward attack on  c7  and, overall, simply has far too much play for the exchange. } )
