[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4( { Having examined the main lines of the Barry, and before we turn our attention to the modern trend for }4...Bg7 5.Nb5 { , there are a few sidelines for Black we should consider. } )
4. Nh5
5. Be5( { This seems even stronger than the fractionally more common }5.Bg5 { . } )( { White retains the bishop, creates a threat, and would be quite happy to obtain easy development after }5...Bg7 6.Bxg7 Nxg7 7.Qd2 { . } )
5. f6
6. Bg3{ Clearly an essential move. Black can now acquire the bishop pair, but White should not be unhappy: we are ready to exploit our superior development to advance in the centre with  e2 - e4  and Black has slightly weakened their kingside. }
6. Nxg3
7. hxg3{ With the  h -file open, White would now especially like to break with  e2 - e4  then get in  Bd3  and Black should probably now clamp down on that break. }
7. f5( 7...c6 { Here White should very much go }8.e4 { , but it would be remiss not to share a beautiful game from the first ever Olympiad: }8.e3?! Bg7 9.Bd3 e5?? 10.Rxh7! { Whoops! And the sacrifices have been no means finished.    }10...Kf7? 11.Bxg6+! Kxg6? 12.Nxe5+! { It's now forced mate, whether via }12...Kxh7 13.Qh5+ Kg8 14.Qf7+ { and  O-O-O  or even more direct means: }12...fxe5 13.Qh5+ Kf6 14.Qxe5+ Kf7 15.Qxg7+ { 1-0, Palau-Te Kolste, London Olympiad 1927. } )
8. e3( { We prefer this modest approach to }8.Ne5 Bg7 9.f4 Be6 { , which didn't seem like too bad a version of a Dutch for Black in Winants-Hovhannisyan, Belgian League 2015. } )
8. Bg7
9. Ne2{ This manoeuvre should leave White with a pleasant edge. The knight will be well placed on  g4 pressing against both  d5  and the black kingside (White may even get  Ng5  in if lucky), and the  c2 - c4  break will also be quick to help place black under pressure. }
