4. Bg7
5. e3
5. Nh5( { Black hunts down the key Barry bishop and this is an improved version of  the  4...Nh5  variation,   since now after }5.Be5 f6 6.Bg3 Nxg3 7.hxg3 { going  e3 - e4  would cost White a tempo.  You may still be happy to play that way, but it's also possible to switch direction and force Black to make a serious concession if he really wants to exchange off the bishop. } )
6. Bg5{ White may now even be able to contemplate ideas of  e3 - e4 , as well as of just  Be2  followed by  Ne5 . }
6. h6
7. Bh4{ Naturally White retains the bishop. }
7. g5{ Consistent, but flawed. }
8. Ne5( { The refutation, and now }8...gxh4? 9.Qxh5 { would fork  f7  and  h4 , thereby simply leaving White doing very well. } )
8. Nf6
9. Bg3
9. c6
10. Bd3{ The most active square for the bishop. The queen will now come to  d2  or  e2  and, while  h2 - h4  should be quite useful, White may also find the  f -pawn a useful one to push. }
10. Be6
11. Qe2{ The queen will be quite usefully placed on  e2  in the event of any  f2 - f4   gxf4 ;  exf4  exchange and now everything is set for castling long. }
11. Nfd7
12. f4{ Not White's only good move, but an active and strong one, threatening  f4 - f5  while angling for a favourable change to the structure. }
12. Nxe5
13. dxe5{ The right way to recapture as  f4 - f5  looms. This advance can always be supported by  Rf1  if needed and from here, Black only lasted a further eight moves in Sklyarov-Nokka, Finnish League 2014. }
