5. Bg4{ A solid approach, looking to exchange off the knight on  f3  before it can get to  e5 . }
6. Qd3{ A perhaps unexpected move, taking advantage of the omission of ... c6  to threaten  Qb5 +. This unpinning approach has been a speciality of that great Barry exponent Mark Hebden. }( { Richard has had a bit of experience with }6.Be2 Bxf3 7.Bxf3 c6 8.O-O O-O { from both sides of the board and can confirm that Black is very solid there. } )( { Interestingly, the latest engines quite like }6.h3!? Bxf3 7.Qxf3 { for White, followed by a quick  g2 - g4 . } )
6. Bxf3
7. Qb5+( { A key intermezzo and, of course }7...c6? { would now be met by }8.Qxb7 { . } )
7. Nbd7
8. gxf3{ The threats of  Qxb7  and  Nxd5  mean that Black is losing a pawn for insufficient compensation. }
