[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. d5
4. Bf4
4. Bg7
5. e3
5. Bg4{ A solid approach, looking to exchange off the knight on  f3  before it can get to  e5 . }
6. Qd3{ A perhaps unexpected move, taking advantage of the omission of ... c6  to threaten  Qb5 +. This unpinning approach has been a speciality of that great Barry exponent Mark Hebden. }( { Richard has had a bit of experience with }6.Be2 Bxf3 7.Bxf3 c6 8.O-O O-O { from both sides of the board and can confirm that Black is very solid there. } )( { Interestingly, the latest engines quite like }6.h3!? Bxf3 7.Qxf3 { for White, followed by a quick  g2 - g4 . } )
6. O-O
7. Ne5( { Possible, of course, now that the knight is no longer pinned. Now White should be quite happy to go }7...-- 8.Nxg4 Nxg4 9.Be2 { to net the bishop pair and }7...Bf5 8.Qb5! { is also a little awkward for Black. } )
7. Be6( { The safest choice as now Black would have everything defended after }8.Qb5 Qc8 { . } )
8. Be2{ Simple development, as White prepares  h2 - h4 , should Black now play slowly, as well as  O-O , which will be useful in the event of a quick ... c5 . }
8. c5
9. O-O{ Not our standard approach, but a good one here. White makes the king safe while keeping  Qb5  ideas in reserve and preparing to bring a rook to  d1 . }( { Here, }9.dxc5 { is fairly well met by }9...Nfd7 { when }10.Nxd7 Nxd7 11.Qb5 Rc8! 12.Qxb7 Nxc5 { begins to look quite scary for White. } )
9. cxd4
10. exd4
10. Nc6{ A standard enough method of development from Black. }
11. Rad1( { White preserves the tension and would now be quite happy to go }11...Bf5 12.Qd2 { . } )( { We'd also welcome }11...Nxe5? 12.dxe5 { when  d5  will fall. Meanwhile,  d4  is overprotected, and so  Qb5  may yet follow. } )
11. Qb6
12. Nxc6( { Often the best approach in such positions as White angles for }12...bxc6 13.Na4 { followed by  Nc5 . } )
12. Qxc6
13. Qe3{ Black is very solid here, but also slightly passive. White will almost certainly want to go  Rfe1  and may find both  h2 - h3  and  Be5  useful in the short term, as well as  a2 - a3  in the event of any ... a6  and ... b5 .  Once  h2 - h3  is in place, one handy regrouping could be  Bd3  followed by  Ne2 , looking to activate the knight via  f4 . }
