9. Nf3( { A new try, keeping pieces on. Instead, }9.Nxd7 Nxd7 10.Bd3 Bxd3 11.cxd3 O-O { seemed fine for Black in Hebden-Krasenkow, Jersey 2013. } )( { The same can be said about }9.Bd3 Nxe5 10.Bxe5 Bxe5 11.dxe5 Nd7 { in the earlier Hebden-McShane, British Championship, Hove 1997. } )( { After }9.Nf3 { , White may still go  h2 - h4  and is ready too to continue development with  Bd3  and  O-O-O . } )
9. Nf6{ Black offers a repetition, just as we saw in a related position in the introductory games and Hebden-Nunn. }
10. Bd3{ White now has ideas of  Bxf5  followed by regrouping with  Ne2 . }( { Black must decide how to trade pieces, since }10...Bg4?! 11.Ne5 { is unlikely to be in their best interests. } )
10. Bxd3
11. cxd3{ An atypical recapture, but it makes decent sense to keep Black out of  e4 . }
11. Nbd7
12. h3{ A handy prophylactic move, enabling the bishop to drop back to  h2  if attacked. }
12. O-O
13. O-O{ Black is pretty solid here, but is probably slightly worse. White will break with  e3 - e4  and/or make a useful advance in  b2 - b4 . As such, perhaps Black might react without delay in the centre. }
13. c5
14. dxc5{ Our favourite capture is a good choice here. }
14. Nxc5
15. Rfc1{ It may not initially look like much, but White's control of  e5  supplies a small but pleasant edge here.  Be5  will help to keep Black bottled up and there are very much ideas too of  Nb5  and even  Nf3 - d4  or  Ne2 - d4 . Another possibility is, of course, that of doubling rooks on the  c -file, perhaps after first forcing the black knight back and activating the queen with  Qd1 - b3 . }( { Play may continue }15...Rc8 16.Be5 { competing for the long diagonal and being quite happy to reset with }16...Ncd7 17.Bh2 { followed by  b2 - b4  and/or  Qd1 - b3 .  If instead }16...Qd7 17.Ne2! { , with  b5  out of bounds, this knight too may appear on  d4  via this square, and White is all now set to double the rooks via  c2  (or  c3 ) and  c1 . }17...Qb5 18.Rc3 { Preparing to double while fully neutralising Black's brief burst of counterplay. }18...Nfd7? 19.Bxg7 Kxg7 20.Rac1 { The pressure down the  c -file is already very awkward for Black. For example, }20...Rcd8 { would run into }21.Rxc5! { , winning two knights for the rook based on the potential check on  c3 . } )
