7. e3{ It's high time to develop the kingside and now White is ready to complete development with  Be2  and  O-O , after which  c2 - c4  may begin to exert some pressure on Black in the centre. Here, we will focus on three setups: }( { 5A) }7...c5 { will be examined  here.  } )( { 5B) }7...c6 { will be examined  here.  } )( { 5C) }7...Ne4 { will be examined  here.   Alternatives to these are rare, if by no means totally uncommon, especially at club and internet levels. } )
7. Bf5
8. Bd3( { It makes sense to challenge Black's most active piece, although if you like to be a little aggressive and provocative, you may wish to explore }8.g4!? { , played once by Arencibia. } )
8. Bxd3
9. cxd3{ This way, White keeps Black out of  e4  and thus their counterplay under control. After  O-O , then  Rc1  may follow, and only after ... c6 ;  Nc3  will White look to start a minority attack with  b2 - b4 . }
9. c5
10. O-O{ Simple chess, housing the king while exploiting the fact that the knights do a fairly good job of covering  d4 . Now  Rc1  and  Qb3  are on their way, and Black would be likely to exchange. }
10. cxd4
11. Nbxd4( { Deviating from the }11.Nfxd4 Nd7 { of Karthik-Gregersen, Reykjavik 2023. White is now set to obtain a grip on the position with  Be5 , so Black may play for ... e5 . } )
11. Nd7
12. Bg3( { Allowing Black a big centre, but actually after }12...e5 13.Nb5 { it wouldn't be going anywhere. } )
12. Qb6
13. Rb1{ Calmly defending  b2 , and now White would quite like to expand with  b2 - b4 ,  Qa4  and  Rfc1 . }
13. e5
14. Ne2( { The  b2-b4  advance remains at the front of White's plans and the engines slightly prefer our chances, in part because neither }14...e4 15.dxe4 dxe4 16.Nfd4 { nor   }14...d4 15.exd4 exd4 16.b4 { is especially troublesome.  Black's centre remains slightly more of a target than a strength in all lines. } )
