10. O-O( { Straightforward play and  a2-a4  may now follow, although if you're feeling in an ambitious mood you may prefer Xiong's }10.Ne5 { , keeping  h3 - h4  ideas on the table. } )
10. Bb7
11. a4( { Threatening to press ahead with  a4-a5  and a much better choice than }11.e4?! { when }11...c5 { secured Black good counterplay in Aronian-Vachier Lagrave, Airthings Masters (rapid) 2020. } )
11. c5
12. a5( { Consistent, seizing space and threatening to expand with  a5-a6  and  Ne5 , although we dare say that a case might also be made for the prophylactic }12.Bh2!? { . } )
12. c4{ This was preferred in Bauer-Mamedov, Internet (blitz) 2020, where White exchanged on  b6 , but should have elected to keep the tension. }
13. Be2( { Now }13...b5? 14.Bxc7 { would win a pawn and White is all set to counter on the queenside in forceful fashion with  b2 - b3 . } )
13. Ne4
14. Nxe4{ Ever a consistent and good exchange. }
14. dxe4
15. Nd2{ Not only is  e4  a dead point, but  c4  is loose. }
15. b5
16. c3{ Halting Black's pawns secures a definite edge. White may strike against  e4  with  Qc2 , can still look to break with  b2 - b3  and may even find a timely  a5 - a6  useful to deflect Black's pieces. }
