16. dxe5{ An essential capture and one you should really try to remember. There just isn't a good alternative due to Black's pressure against  d4  and ... Ne3  ideas, but now White is all set, if allowed, to take control with  Qd4 . }( { As this line was recommended on Gawain Jones's excellent and detailed 'Lifetime Repertoires: King's Indian Defense' two-part course, you may wish to see how Jones wants to continue here, although we would be very impressed if a club-level player or simply any opponent surprised by the Barry got anything like so far down this critical line. }16...Bxe4 17.fxe4 Bxe5! { Now Jones only looks at }18.Bxe5 Qh4+ 19.Kd2 Qg5+ { when White should repeat with }20.Ke1 { .  But what about if you're not playing a higher-rated opponent or don't want a draw? }{   }18.Qf3!? Bxg3+ 19.Qxg3 Re8 20.Bd3 { Holding on to  e4  for now while preparing to go long. }20...Nf4 { . Now, }21.O-O-O Rxe4! 22.Bxe4 Ne2+ { leads to a simplification we can try to avoid with   }21.Bc2!? { . Will opponents now manage to find another tactic? }21...Qh4! { Only this move will do for Black. }22.Qxh4 Nxg2+ 23.Kf2 Nxh4 24.Rad1 { An unbalanced, roughly level endgame has arisen. White has the better minor piece, but also the worse structure. He should be looking to activate the rook down the  d -file to  d4 ,  d5  or ideally  d7 , as well as begin to make good use of the queenside majority with  c3 - c4 - c5 . } )
