[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3( { Our favourite knight development does, of course, prepare  e2-e4  and we will now examine what happens when Black neglects to rule it out with }3...d5 { . That is Black's most popular move, but in practice }3...Bg7 { is seen almost half as often. For a Pirc player, going }3...Bg7 { is fine, but plenty of opponents even in 2023 are caught out by the Barry and so continue King's Indian style with }3...Bg7 { , failing to realise that White's  c -pawn is still on  c2  and so Pirc not King's Indian waters lie ahead. } )
3. c5( { A creative and independent try, but unfortunately for Black, White is not forced to enter the Schmid Benoni with }4.d5 { . } )
4. dxc5{ Our favourite capture in the  main line of the Barry  is also a good one here. White fights for the initiative and already plans to disrupt Black's development with  e2 - e4 - e5  if allowed. }
4. Qa5
5. e4( { Fearless play, but even when used as a gambit the central advance is a good one. White threatens  6.e5 , possibly even followed by  e5-e6  and  Qd4 , will find }d4 { a good square for the queen in any case and should be quite content with a significant early lead in development after }5...Qxc5 6.Be3 { . Likewise, }{   }5...Bg7 6.e5 { is quite pleasant, as we'll see  next  via a   }4...Bg7 5.e4 Qa5 6.e5 { move order. } )
5. Nxe4
6. Qd4( { With a double threat and now }6...Nxc3? 7.Qxh8 { simply wins material, as the discovered checks can be safely met by  8.c3 . As such, the knight must skip backwards. } )
6. Nf6
7. b4( { With tempo. Now the pawn on  c5  is overprotected and Black must be careful: }7...Qc7? 8.Nb5 Qd8 9.Qe5 { would not be wise. } )
7. Qd8
8. Bb2( 8.Bc4 { was also a good move in H.Vogel-Smokina, Dresden 2004, but with the fianchetto White menaces  Nd5 , after which  O-O-O  and  Qh4  may well secure a strong initiative. } )
8. Bg7
9. Qh4{ Stepping off the long diagonal. White's very active position is an attractive one, with ideas of  Nd5  or  Ne4  high on the agenda, as well as  O-O-O , after which even  Bc4  (or perhaps  Bb5 +) and  Rhe1  may follow. }
