1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3( { Our favourite knight development does, of course, prepare  e2-e4  and we will now examine what happens when Black neglects to rule it out with }3...d5 { . That is Black's most popular move, but in practice }3...Bg7 { is seen almost half as often. For a Pirc player, going }3...Bg7 { is fine, but plenty of opponents even in 2023 are caught out by the Barry and so continue King's Indian style with }3...Bg7 { , failing to realise that White's  c -pawn is still on  c2  and so Pirc not King's Indian waters lie ahead. } )
3. c5( { A creative and independent try, but unfortunately for Black, White is not forced to enter the Schmid Benoni with }4.d5 { . } )
4. dxc5{ Our favourite capture in the  main line of the Barry  is also a good one here. White fights for the initiative and already plans to disrupt Black's development with  e2 - e4 - e5  if allowed. }
4. Bg7
5. e4{ Naturally White would like to inconvenience Black's development with  e4 - e5 . }
5. Qa5
6. e5{ Since  Qd4  is in reserve, White is able to press ahead so. }
6. Ne4
7. Qd4( { Forcing the pace and, of course, }7...Nxc5? 8.b4 { would not be good for Black. } )
7. Nxc3
8. Bd2{ A key follow-up, ensuring White will regain the piece without destroying his structure in the process. Now  Bxc3  followed by  O-O-O  and perhaps  Qh4  beckons, and in any case Black is clearly worse. }
8. Nc6
9. Qxc3{ White is quite happy to exchange queens and so preserve the powerful, cramping pawn on  e5 . }
9. Qxc3
10. Bxc3{ Holding on to the extra pawn and a clear plus. White is now all set to castle long, after which it may well be time to involve Harry, the  h -pawn. }
