1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3( { Our favourite knight development does, of course, prepare  e2-e4  and we will now examine what happens when Black neglects to rule it out with }3...d5 { . That is Black's most popular move, but in practice }3...Bg7 { is seen almost half as often. For a Pirc player, going }3...Bg7 { is fine, but plenty of opponents even in 2023 are caught out by the Barry and so continue King's Indian style with }3...Bg7 { , failing to realise that White's  c -pawn is still on  c2  and so Pirc not King's Indian waters lie ahead. } )
3. Bg7{ Black completes the fianchetto and especially at lower levels you can expect to see this approach in a fair number of your games. }
4. e4{ Naturally White expands in the centre while threatening  e4 - e5 , hence why Black almost always now aims to dissuade that advance. }
4. O-O{ Richard Reti once played this way and perhaps your club and internet opponents occasionally will too, but we should be delighted with the powerful initiative White can now obtain. }
5. e5
5. Ne8
6. h4( { Put that in your pipe and smoke it! White exploits his early significant space advantage to launch an early attack. Now, }6...c5 { can again be well met by }7.dxc5 { , so Black is likely to either counter in the centre or slightly desperately try to keep lines closed. } )
6. h5
7. g4{ This dangerous advance is still to be wheeled out over the board, but secures a strong initiative. }
7. hxg4
8. Ng5{ Both  Qxg4  and especially  h4 - h5  loom large on the kingside. }
8. d6
9. h5( { This is even stronger than }9.e6 { as White threatens both  hxg6  and  h5 - h6 . } )
9. dxe5
10. hxg6{ With  Bc4 (+) in reserve and Black's position collapsing on  f7 , White is already winning. }
