3. Nc3( { Our favourite knight development does, of course, prepare  e2-e4  and we will now examine what happens when Black neglects to rule it out with }3...d5 { . That is Black's most popular move, but in practice }3...Bg7 { is seen almost half as often. For a Pirc player, going }3...Bg7 { is fine, but plenty of opponents even in 2023 are caught out by the Barry and so continue King's Indian style with }3...Bg7 { , failing to realise that White's  c -pawn is still on  c2  and so Pirc not King's Indian waters lie ahead. } )
3. Bg7{ Black completes the fianchetto and especially at lower levels you can expect to see this approach in a fair number of your games. }
4. e4{ Naturally White expands in the centre while threatening  e4 - e5 , hence why Black almost always now aims to dissuade that advance. }
4. d5{ The best of Black's independent tries, countering vigorously in the centre. }
5. e5( { Seizing the space on offer must be critical, although if you're happy with a small pull and manoeuvring struggle, }5.exd5 Nxd5 6.Ne4 { would retain pieces and is a reasonable choice. } )
5. Ne4
6. Nxe4( { Taking up the challenge, although if you have some experience of playing against the French Winawer you may prefer }6.Bd3 Nxc3 7.bxc3 c5 8.O-O { . } )( { Those who like to explore uncharted byways may wish to look into }6.h4!? { . } )
6. dxe4
7. Ng5( { This position is also known from the Modern Defence with the inclusion of  h2-h3  and  ...c6 :   }1.d4 g6 2.e4 Bg7 3.Nc3 c6 4.Nf3 d5 5.h3 Nf6 6.e5 Ne4 7.Nxe4 dxe4 8.Ng5 { , where Black now goes ... c5  in any case. } )
7. c5
8. e6( { Arguably the most scary move for Black to have to face as White fights hard for the initiative. A great many alternatives have been tested and we will just note that the correspondence world has quite liked }8.f4!? { , while }8.d5 Bxe5 9.Nxe4 O-O 10.c3 { was pretty sensible and Hebden's first choice here in Hebden-McShane, Kilkenny 1998. } )
8. Bxe6
9. Nxe6
9. fxe6
10. dxc5( { Without a knight on  g5 , it's important to re-establish material equality here as }10.Bc4 cxd4 11.Bxe6? Qd6 { would only help Black. } )( { White now threatens  Qxd8+ , as well as  Bc4 , and wouldn't mind }10...Qxd1+ 11.Kxd1 { when the king will be quite safe on  c2  after  c2 - c3  and both  Bc4  and  Rhe1  would follow. } )
10. Qa5+
11. c3( { The bishops are now ready to spring out to  e3  and  c4 , while }11...Qxc5?! { is fairly well met by }12.Qb3 { , so Black should increase the pressure against  c5 . } )
11. Nd7
12. Bd2{ Putting  b2 - b4  on to the agenda as a powerful advance. }
12. Qxc5
13. Qb3{ With  Be3  next up, the bishop pair and several weak black pawns to target on the light squares, White enjoyed full compensation in Hebden-Conquest, British Championship, Torquay 1998. }
