1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3( { Our favourite knight development does, of course, prepare  e2-e4  and we will now examine what happens when Black neglects to rule it out with }3...d5 { . That is Black's most popular move, but in practice }3...Bg7 { is seen almost half as often. For a Pirc player, going }3...Bg7 { is fine, but plenty of opponents even in 2023 are caught out by the Barry and so continue King's Indian style with }3...Bg7 { , failing to realise that White's  c -pawn is still on  c2  and so Pirc not King's Indian waters lie ahead. } )
3. Bg7{ Black completes the fianchetto and especially at lower levels you can expect to see this approach in a fair number of your games. }
4. e4{ Naturally White expands in the centre while threatening  e4 - e5 , hence why Black almost always now aims to dissuade that advance. }
4. d6
5. Bf4( { Our favourite square for the bishop, fighting for control of  e5 , and a move which is likely to surprise many opponents. White usually opts for one of }5.Be2 { , }5.h3 { or }5.Be3 { , with }5.Bf4 { also somewhat less common than }5.Bg5 { , }5.Bc4 { and even }5.Bd3 { . White already hints at immediate aggression with  e4 - e5 , as well as an aggressive development scheme in  Qd2  followed by  O-O-O  and  Bh6 . Black players may well react with the same setup they deploy against }5.Be3 { , and here we will focus on: } )( { 6A) }5...O-O { will be examined  here.  } )( { 6B) }5...c6 { will be examined  here.  } )( { 6C) }5...Nc6 { will be examined  here.   Other options are rare, and should be welcomed. } )
5. a6
6. Qd2{ The logical follow-up, facilitating  O-O-O , as well as  Bh6 . }
6. b5
7. Bh6{ White should be happy to up the ante with this. Would an opponent now dare to castle kingside? }
7. O-O
8. Bxg7{ Exchanging before ... b4  becomes an issue. }
8. Kxg7
9. Bd3( { This threatened to exploit White's superior development and favoured him in K.Darga-B.Larsen, Beverwijk 1967, and several subsequent games, since }9...b4 10.Ne2 { would only drive the knight over to join in the kingside attack. } )
9. Nc6
10. e5{ Even here White should advance so since there's a powerful pawn sacrifice brewing. }
10. dxe5
11. dxe5
11. Ng4
12. O-O-O{ White threatens to cause disruption with  Qe1 , as well as just defend  e5  with  Rhe1  and now Black has usually declined the pawn in practice. }
12. b4
13. Rhe1{ First played in 2005, this is a strong temporary piece sacrifice with which White has scored well. Now  e5  is overprotected, meaning  h2 - h3  is an issue, as well as  Na4 , and Black shouldn't really touch the piece: }
13. Rb8
14. Na4{ Threatening  Qf4 , as well as  h2 - h3 . }
14. Qd5
15. b3{ It's important to keep  a2  and the white king safe, even at the cost of  e5 . }
15. Ngxe5
16. Nxe5
16. Nxe5
17. Bf1{ A perhaps unexpected retreat, but a fairly strong one, making good use of the centralised nature of both white rooks. }
17. Qxd2+
18. Rxd2{ As practice has shown, White enjoys promising compensation. Black is under pressure down the  e -file, White always has  f2 - f4  if needed and  Nc5  will begin to exploit the holes in Black's position, while targeting both  a6  and  d7 . }
