17. Bc4{ Threatening not just the rook, but also  Ng5  and even  g2 - g4 . With such threats, as well as the massively better coordination, White already enjoys far too strong an initiative for the piece. }( { For example: }17...Rf8 18.Bd5 { Finally White gets around to creating a pin on the  h1 - a8  diagonal. }18...Bd7 19.g4 { With the black king lacking a single safe square, this is even stronger than  Ng5 , and just leaves White doing extremely well, since Black can only try to run, not successfully hide. }19...h6 20.h4 Kh7? 21.Ng5+! { A hammer blow. }21...hxg5 22.hxg5 { Black is two pieces up, but won't survive with such an exposed king and faced with such a threat as  gxf6  followed by  Rh1 +. } )
