5. O-O{ Black's most popular move by some margin, just as it is after  5.Be3 , to which play may now transpose if White follows up their next move with  Bh6 . }
6. Qd2( { Placing ideas of both  Bh6  and  O-O-O  firmly on the table in thematic fashion. Note too how compared to the  Be3  lines, }6...e5? { would now just lose a pawn to }7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Bxe5 { , and if }8...Qxd2+ 9.Nxd2 { . } )( { We've already seen }6...a6 7.Bh6 { (thematically going for that bishop exchange) }7...b5 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { via a   }5...a6 6.Qd2 b5 7.Bh6 O-O 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { move order  here.  } )
6. Nc6( { Nepomniachtchi has played this way. Black hints at  ...Nxd4  and also prepares to meet }7.Bh6 { with }7...e5 { . As such, White should keep calm and castle. } )
7. O-O-O( { Now, }7...e5? 8.dxe5 { will merely cost Black a pawn. Meanwhile, White is ready to go  8.Bh6  or even  8.h4 , so Black should continue to counter against  d4 . } )
7. Bg4
8. Qe3{ Alexander Grischuk and Mark Hebden's preference and quite a neat little move. The queen skips off the  d -file to prevent ... e5  and also prepare to recapture on  f3  in the event of any exchange there. Meanwhile, White is all set to complete development with  Be2  then go  Bh6 , and may well even go  9.e5  if Black now reacts in slow fashion. }
8. Nd7
9. Bh6( { This direct approach seems to be even stronger than Rauf Mamedov's }9.Bg5!? { . White simply prepares to charge the  h -pawn down the board, while taking ... Nxd4  off the agenda. } )
9. Bxf3
10. gxf3{ With  h2 - h4 - h5  still on the way, we would certainly prefer to take White here. }
10. e5
11. Bxg7
11. Kxg7
12. dxe5( { An important exchange and much better option than }12.d5 Nd4! { . White looks to be doing very well with both the front  f - and  h -pawns primed to advance and Black may even find  Bh3  something of an issue in case of recapturing with the  d -pawn. } )
