4. d6
5. Bf4
5. O-O{ Black's most popular move by some margin, just as it is after  5.Be3 , to which play may now transpose if White follows up their next move with  Bh6 . }
6. Qd2( { Placing ideas of both  Bh6  and  O-O-O  firmly on the table in thematic fashion. Note too how compared to the  Be3  lines, }6...e5? { would now just lose a pawn to }7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Bxe5 { , and if }8...Qxd2+ 9.Nxd2 { . } )( { We've already seen }6...a6 7.Bh6 { (thematically going for that bishop exchange) }7...b5 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { via a   }5...a6 6.Qd2 b5 7.Bh6 O-O 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { move order  here.  } )
6. c5
7. dxc5( { Our standard approach in such scenarios and as }7...Qa5? 8.cxd6 { would now make little sense for Black, offering the queen exchange is advisable. } )
7. dxc5
8. O-O-O( { There's no good way of avoiding the exchange of queens so we should force it on our terms, while hoping that Black might do something careless like }8...Qb6? { , which walks into }9.e5 { followed by  Nd5 . } )
8. Qxd2+
9. Rxd2( { Preparing to double rooks on the  d -file once the bishop has been developed, while also usefully covering  f 2 and so meaning that }9...Ng4? { could now be met by }10.Nd5 { . } )
9. Nc6
10. h3{ Keeping Black out of  g4  for good and so preparing  e4 - e5 , as well as  g2 - g4 . Perhaps Black can equalise with care here, but White's position looks slightly the easier to handle. }
10. Nd4{ This must be fairly critical and was seen as many as three times in a 2021 speed match between Nihal Sarin and Olexandr Bortnyk. }
11. Be3( { Forcing the knight from  d4  and approved by the engines, who also quite like }11.Nxd4!? cxd4 12.Rxd4 Nh5 13.Be3 Bxd4 14.Bxd4 { , swapping the exchange for a pawn and all the dark squares. } )
11. Nxf3
12. gxf3{ White not only threatens  Bxc5 , but may be able to make something of the weakened  d5 -square. }( { Indeed, Bortnyk was quickly in trouble in one game after }12...Nd7? 13.Nd5 { . } )
12. b6{ Prudently shoring up  c5  while preparing ... Bb7  to counter any ideas of  e4 - e5  in conjunction with  f3 - f4  and  Bg2 . }
13. Bc4{ The most active square for the bishop, threatening  14.e5  followed by exploiting the  d5 -square and  f3 - f4 . }
13. Bb7
14. Rhd1{ Nihal Sarin twice went on to win from here and White certainly enjoys a pleasant edge, with full control of the open file, the ability to clamp down on any counterplay with  a4 - a5 , as well as to probe with  Nb5 - c7 , and the option of a useful enough looking central advance in  e4 - e5  followed by  f3 - f4 . }
