9. h4( { White has often preferred  9.Kb1  here, but simply intending to blow open the  h -file with }9...-- 10.Bxg7 Kxg7 11.h5 { is a much more dangerous strategy. } )
9. Bxh6
10. Qxh6{ Once again, both  Ng5  and  h4 - h5  loom. }
10. Ng4
11. Qd2( { A necessary retreat, but now  12.h5  is back on and White can meet }11...h5 { well enough by }12.Ng5 { . } )
11. b5
12. h5{ Ignoring Black as White threatens  hxg6  in conjunction with  Qg5  to transfer the queen to the  h -file. }
12. b4
13. Nb1( { A retreat, but a necessary one to keep the white king safe and now }13...Ndf6 14.Bd3 Nxh5 15.e5 { threatened  Rxh5  and left Black under heavy pressure in Morozov-Kiselev, Voronezh 2008. What happens though in case of taking the pawn? } )
13. Qxa2
14. hxg6( { Clearly }14...hxg6? 15.Qg5 { would now be pretty good news for White. } )
14. fxg6
15. Qxb4( { Simple chess, threatening }15...-- 16.Bc4+ { , as well as }16.Nc3 { , and if }16...Qa1+? 17.Kd2 { , trapping the black queen. White enjoys the safer king, superior coordination and must be clearly for choice. } )
