6. Qd2( { Placing ideas of both  Bh6  and  O-O-O  firmly on the table in thematic fashion. Note too how compared to the  Be3  lines, }6...e5? { would now just lose a pawn to }7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Bxe5 { , and if }8...Qxd2+ 9.Nxd2 { . } )( { We've already seen }6...a6 7.Bh6 { (thematically going for that bishop exchange) }7...b5 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { via a   }5...a6 6.Qd2 b5 7.Bh6 O-O 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { move order  here.  } )
6. c6{ Black's most common response, preparing to obtain some counterplay on the queenside with ... b5  and/or ... Qa5 , if by no means whatsoever forced. }
7. Bh6{ Thematically offering an exchange of the dark-squared bishops, as well as the prelude to quickly going  h2 - h4 - h5 . This position can, of course, also come about via a  Be3  move order. }( { You may also wish to consider }7.h4!? { , and if }7...h5 8.Bh6 { , which has been seen somewhat less often. } )
7. Bg4{ A natural enough attempt to obtain some counterplay, if also quite a slow policy. }
8. O-O-O( { Consistent with  our approach  of meeting   }6...Bg4 { with }7.O-O-O { . } )( { However, here a pretty decent case can also be made for }8.h4!? { . After }8.O-O-O { ,  h2 - h4 - h5  is very much on the cards, so Black has usually elected to react. } )
8. b5
9. Bxg7
9. Kxg7
10. h3{ The best policy here, playing to remove both black bishops. }
10. Bxf3
11. gxf3{ Here,  h3 - h4 - h5  is very much still on the cards and White can always strengthen any attack by bringing his knight over and into it via  e2 . Meanwhile if Black reacts to  h4  with ... h5  then White will look to crash through in the centre and down the  g -file after  Bd3  and  f3 - f4  followed by  e4 - e5  and/or  f4 - f5 . }
11. Nbd7
12. Ne2( { Here, we quite like this prophylactic and regrouping move instead of the immediate }12.h4 { . White takes ... b4  and ... Qa5  off the table for now and the knight will be very well placed on  g3 , supporting both  h3 - h4 - h5  and  f3 - f4 . } )
