2. g6
3. Nc3
3. Bg7
4. e4
4. d6
5. Bf4
5. O-O{ Black's most popular move by some margin, just as it is after  5.Be3 , to which play may now transpose if White follows up their next move with  Bh6 . }
6. Qd2( { Placing ideas of both  Bh6  and  O-O-O  firmly on the table in thematic fashion. Note too how compared to the  Be3  lines, }6...e5? { would now just lose a pawn to }7.dxe5 dxe5 8.Bxe5 { , and if }8...Qxd2+ 9.Nxd2 { . } )( { We've already seen }6...a6 7.Bh6 { (thematically going for that bishop exchange) }7...b5 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { via a   }5...a6 6.Qd2 b5 7.Bh6 O-O 8.Bxg7 Kxg7 9.Bd3 { move order  here.  } )
6. c6{ Black's most common response, preparing to obtain some counterplay on the queenside with ... b5  and/or ... Qa5 , if by no means whatsoever forced. }
7. Bh6{ Thematically offering an exchange of the dark-squared bishops, as well as the prelude to quickly going  h2 - h4 - h5 . This position can, of course, also come about via a  Be3  move order. }( { You may also wish to consider }7.h4!? { , and if }7...h5 8.Bh6 { , which has been seen somewhat less often. } )
7. b5{ Consistent, threatening ... b4  and seen in roughly half the games which have reached this position. }
8. Bd3{ Developing while securing  e4  against the threat of ... b4 . With good and harmonious development, White is now all set to drive Black backwards with  e4 - e5  in the next move if allowed. }
8. Bg4{ Black's most popular move and engine-approved, looking to disrupt before  e4 - e5  lands. }
9. h4( { Simply ignoring Black to get on with it on the kingside where  h4-h5  is actually already a threat and, once again, }9...b4 10.Ne2 { would only serve to drive the white knight over and into the attack. } )
9. Bxf3
10. gxf3
10. e5
11. h5( { The most direct, although you may also be happy to settle for an edge with }11.Ne2 { . With the text, White simply wants to land the queen on  h6  once again, as well as complete development with  O-O-O , thereby bringing another potential attacker into play in the shape of the queen's rook. } )
11. exd4
12. Ne2{ This strong retreat prepares  O-O-O  even more than  Nxd4 . }
12. c5
13. O-O-O{ White's atack is so strong that even this piece sacrifice is possible, and in any case  Ng3  and  Rdg1  are now on their way. }
13. c4
14. Nxd4
14. cxd3
15. Bxg7{ Already Black might well resign since the bishop can't be recaptured. }
15. Kxg7
16. hxg6( { Simple chess and deadly chess too. Either  Qh6+  or }16...fxg6 17.Ne6+ { is going to clean Black up. } )
