5. Bf4
5. c6{ Black delays committing the king and prepares immediate counterplay on the queenside. }
6. Qd2( { Consistent, and White would now be quite happy to go }6...-- 7.Bh6 { if allowed, either leading to attacking chances after }7...O-O { or to the queen taking up a strong role while preventing Black from castling if }7...Bxh6 8.Qxh6 { . } )
6. Qa5( { Activating the queen and setting a small trap: do not fall for }7.Bh6? Bxh6 8.Qxh6 Nxe4 { . } )
7. h4( { Played anyhow and this bold advance is likely to stun opponents. White is, of course, angling for }7...O-O 8.Bh6! { with a transposition back to   }5...O-O 6.Qd2 c6 7.Bh6 Qa5 8.h4 { , as we saw in the realm of  Chapter 6A,  while also looking to make a useful aggressive move before going  O-O-O . } )( { In practice the immediate }7.O-O-O { has been more common, as has been }7.Bd3 { when White may well settle for a small edge with }7...O-O 8.h3 { followed by  O-O . } )
7. Bg4
8. e5( { With tempo against  f6  and  d6 . Instead, }8.Nh2!? { would be another way to attempt to exploit the inclusion of  7.h4 . } )
8. dxe5
9. Nxe5{ Now  Bc4  becomes an issue for Black, as well as just  Nxg4  and  h4 - h5 . }
9. Be6
10. Bc4( { Playing to destroy Black's structure on  e6  or to enjoy control and a likely edge after }10...Nd5 11.Bg3 { . } )
10. Bxc4
11. Nxc4{ The pawn doesn't look so out of place on  h4  here with White striving to seize the initiative. Next move though White will likely castle long or return the knight to  e5 . }
