1. d4
1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. g6
3. Nc3
3. Bg7
4. e4
4. d6
5. Bf4
5. Nc6{ Striking back in the centre, against  d4  and with ideas of ... e5 , makes some sense when White's bishop is on  f4 . }
6. Qd2( { Consistent, placing  Bh6  on the agenda. Now, Black has often played }6...O-O { when }7.O-O-O { transposes to   }5...O-O 6.Qd2 Nc6 7.O-O-O { , as we saw back in  Chapter 6A.  } )
6. a6
7. O-O-O{ A consistent approach and now pinning as Black is the policy recommended by Vjekoslav Nemec on the second version of his popular 'The Uncompromising Modern Defense' course. }
7. Bg4
8. Bh6( { We prefer this to }8.Be2 { . White frees  e3  for the queen and can still aim to attack after 8... O-O  }{ . } )
8. Bxh6
9. Qxh6
9. e5{ Reacting in the centre must be critical, especially as Black cannot, of course, castle kingside. }
10. dxe5
10. Nxe5
11. Nxe5( { Wowsers. This sacrifice may well surprise opponents, but is in any case a decent one. However, it's also quite possible to retain control and a decent setup with the calm }11.Qe3 { . } )
11. Bxd1
12. Nxf7{ The point of White's play as Black pretty much must take the knight. }
12. Kxf7
13. Bc4+( { Now }13...d5? { wouldn't be so clever, as }14.Rxd1 { keeps Black pinned after all. } )
13. Ke8
14. Rxd1{ Stockfish assesses White's compensation at around '0.50', a value which we wonder shouldn't be higher. Black's king is stuck in the centre and can never castle, while White has a pawn for the exchange and the initiative. Black can avoid being killed by  15.e5 , but in any case White will enjoy promising compensation after getting in  f2 - f4 , possibly first after dropping the queen back to  e3  or even  d2 . }
