1. d4( { The Barry Attack is an anti-King's Indian weapon, but there is the odd King's Indian exponent who prefers a }1...Nf6 2.Nf3 d6 { move order when }3.Nc3 { is still a good weapon, as we'll now see. } )
1. d6
2. Nf3( { You may well prefer }2.e4 { here, but the knight development is also a good one, preventing ... e5 . } )( { After }2.Nf3 { , Black's two main moves are }2...Nf6 { , transposing to our main line in this section, and }2...g6 { , when we'll see }3.e4 Bg7 4.Nc3 { in our next bonus section on  the Modern.  } )
2. Bg4{ The Wade Defence. This used to be considered a reasonable try by Black to unbalance the position, but is nowadays known to lead to a fairly pleasant edge for White - and without requiring too much theoretical knowledge. }
3. e4{ White should seize the space on offer and enable the queen to recapture on  f3 . }
3. Nc6
4. d5{ Seizing space and provoking Black forwards... }
4. Ne5
5. Nxe5{ A classic queen sacrifice. }
5. Bxd1
6. Bb5+{ The point. }
6. c6
7. dxc6( { White will now favourably regain the queen, as with }7...a6 8.c7+ { , since it can’t easily escape. } )
7. Qa5+
8. Nc3
8. O-O-O
9. Nc4{ Forcing the pace. }
9. Qb4
10. a3
10. Qc5
11. Be3{ White’s point, developing the final minor piece with tempo. }
11. Qh5
12. cxb7+
12. Kxb7
13. Na5+{ Next, White will pick up a second piece for the queen with  Rxd1  and simply enjoys a very strong attack. }
