2. Nf3( { You may well prefer }2.e4 { here, but the knight development is also a good one, preventing ... e5 . } )( { After }2.Nf3 { , Black's two main moves are }2...Nf6 { , transposing to our main line in this section, and }2...g6 { , when we'll see }3.e4 Bg7 4.Nc3 { in our next bonus section on  the Modern.  } )
2. Bg4{ The Wade Defence. This used to be considered a reasonable try by Black to unbalance the position, but is nowadays known to lead to a fairly pleasant edge for White - and without requiring too much theoretical knowledge. }
3. e4{ White should seize the space on offer and enable the queen to recapture on  f3 . }
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ Securing  e4  ahead of prodding the bishop with  h2 - h3 . }( { Now, }4...c6 5.h3 Bxf3 6.Qxf3 e5 7.Be3 { followed by  O-O-O  and/or  g2 - g4  supplied another very pleasant edge in Palliser-Wright, Leeds (rapid) 2012. } )
4. e6
5. h3{ The thematic kick as White looks to acquire the bishop pair. We should just be happy with the two bishops and a decent centre after an exchange on  f3 . }
5. Bh5
6. Qe2( { An important move and the reason why the Wade Defence is under something of a cloud. White not only threatens  Qb5+ , but with  e4  overprotected is simply ready to expand in powerful fashion with }6...-- 7.g4 Bg6 8.h4 { . } )
6. c6
7. g4
7. Bg6
8. h4{ Continuing the thematic and powerful expansion. }
8. h5
9. g5
9. Nfd7
10. d5( { Thematic expansion, if by no means White's only good move here. After }10.d5 { , we are all set to target  e6  after exchanging pawns there followed by  Nd4 . } )
10. cxd5
11. exd5
11. e5{ At least this way Black manages to keep lines closed. }
12. Be3{ This left White clearly for choice in Bok-Pakleza, Airthings Masters Play-In (rapid) 2023, being all set to complete development with  O-O-O  and  Bh3 . White's space advantage is a pretty useful asset and  Nd2  is also likely to prove quite strong, followed by  Nde4  and/or  f2 - f4 . }
