1. Nf6
2. Nf3
2. d6
3. Nc3( { No Old Indian for Black today as White prepares  e2-e4 . Now, }3...g6 4.e4 { would take play back into the world of the Pirc and  Chapter Six.  } )
3. Nbd7( { Black angles for }4.e4 e5 { and a Philidor Defence. You may well be happy with that, whether followed by the main line with }5.Bc4 { or Shirov's }5.g4 { , but for those that aren't or highly creative types White does have another, much less common move. } )
4. Bf4( { Yuriy Kuzubov has used this on more than one occasion to prevent }4...e5 { as }5.dxe5 { just wins a pawn. } )( { White is still happy with a Pirc transposition after }4...g6 5.e4 { . } )
4. Nh5
5. Bg5( { Angling for even more than the immediate }5.Bd2 { , as Alexander Grischuk has used. } )
5. h6
6. Bd2( { Retaining an important bishop, something which }6.Bh4 g5 { wouldn't. After }6.Bd2 { , the pawn on  h6  might prove to become a target if Black goes Pirc style with }6...g6 7.e4 { . } )
6. e5
7. e4( { Threatening to win a pawn with }7...-- 8.dxe5 dxe5 9.Nxe5 { while }7...exd4?! 8.Nxd4 { would also inconvenience the knight on the rim. } )
7. Nhf6
8. Rg1{ This is a most unusual version of a Philidor that deserves some testing. White's plan is a typically aggressive one:  g2 - g4 ,  h2 - h4  and  g4 - g5 , with  Qe2  and  O-O-O  also likely to be useful in some lines. }
