1. d4
1. g6
2. e4{ Taking over the centre without delay must, of course, be the critical way to meet the Modern. }
2. Bg7
3. Nf3( { Here, before  Nc3  to dissuade any  ...d5  ideas. }3...d5?! 4.exd5 { looks quite pleasant for White after }4...Qxd5 5.c4 { and   }4...Nf6 5.c4!? { . } )
3. c5{ The so-called Sniper. }
4. dxc5{ Our favourite capture is also a pretty good one here, dragging the black queen into play at an early stage. }
4. Qa5+
5. c3{ White not only facilitates  b2 - b4  while blocking the check, but is now set to zoom the queen's knight into play via  a3 . }
5. Qxc5
6. Na3{ Already  Nb5  in conjunction with  Be3  is something of an issue for Black. }
6. Bxc3+{ A critical reaction, if also a rather greedy choice and one White should be delighted to see. }
7. bxc3
7. Qxc3+
8. Qd2{ White wants to retain his powerful knight on  a3  and is quite happy to sacrifice the exchange. }
8. Qxa1
9. Nb5{ With a certain threat. }
9. Na6
10. Bc4{ White is the exchange and two pawns down, but also enjoys a very strong initiative, with the immediate idea that of  O-O  followed by trapping the black queen with  Bb2 . }
10. Qg7
11. e5{ Fighting against Black's hopes of getting in both ... d6  and ... Nf6 . White is now all set to go  Bb2  and  O-O , and Black's position is quite frankly a mess, assessed as '-4' by the engines. }
